# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adx-florence
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The program began in 1968 as a bi-weekly television show hosted by Mike Wallace and Harry Reasoner.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The two sat on opposite sides of the cream-colored set, though the set's color was later changed to black, the color still in use.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The show used a large stopwatch during transition periods and highlighted its topics through chroma key—both techniques are still used.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] In 1972, the program began airing from 6:00 p.m. to 7:00 p.m.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Eastern time, although this time was sometimes disrupted by broadcasting of NFL games on Sundays.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Since then, the show has generally kept the Sunday evening format, although the start time has occasionally been shifted.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The program generally starts at 7:00 p.m.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] If sports programming is airing that afternoon, *60 Minutes* starts at 7:30 p.m.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The show is hosted by correspondents who do not share screen time with each other.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Full-time hosts include Lesley Stahl and Bill Whitaker.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Several spinoffs have been made, including international formats of the show.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Starting in 2006, the background color was changed to red, the title text color changed to white, and the stopwatch was shifted to the upright position.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The program employed a magazine format similar to that of the Canadian program *W5*, which had premiered two years earlier.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] It pioneered many of the most important investigative journalism procedures and techniques, including re-editing interviews, hidden cameras, and "gotcha journalism" visits to the home or office of an investigative subject.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Similar programs sprang up in Australia and Canada during the 1970s, as well as on local television news.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Initially, *60 Minutes* aired as a bi-weekly show hosted by Mike Wallace and Harry Reasoner debuting on September 24, 1968, and alternating weeks with other CBS News productions on Tuesday evenings at 10:00 p.m.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] A meditation by Wallace and Reasoner on the relation between perception and reality.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Wallace said that the show aimed to "reflect reality".
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The first "magazine-cover" chroma key was a photo of two helmeted policemen (for the Clark interview segment).
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Wallace and Reasoner sat in chairs on opposite sides of the set, which had a cream-colored backdrop; the more famous black backdrop (which is still used as of 2020) did not appear until the following year.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The logo was in Helvetica type with the word "Minutes" spelled in all lower-case letters; the logo most associated with the show (rendered in Eurostile type with "Minutes" spelled in uppercase) did not appear until about 1974.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Further, to extend the magazine motif, the producers added a "Vol. xx, No. xx" to the title display on the chroma key; modeled after the volume and issue number identifications featured in print magazines, this was used until about 1971.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The trademark stopwatch, however, did not appear on the inaugural broadcast; it would not debut until several episodes later.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Alpo dog food was the sole sponsor of the first program.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Don Hewitt, who had been a producer of the *CBS Evening News* with Walter Cronkite, sought out Wallace as a stylistic contrast to Reasoner.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] According to one historian of the show, the idea of the format was to make the hosts the reporters, to always feature stories that were of national importance but focused upon individuals involved with, or in conflict with, those issues, and to limit the reports' airtime to around 13 minutes.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] However, the initial season was troubled by lack of network confidence, as the program did not garner ratings much higher than that of other CBS News documentaries.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] *60 Minutes* struggled under that stigma during its first three years.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Changes to *60 Minutes* came fairly early in the program's history.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] When Reasoner left CBS to co-anchor ABC's evening newscast (he would return to CBS and *60 Minutes* in 1978), Morley Safer joined the team in 1970, and he took over Reasoner's duties of reporting less aggressive stories.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] By 1971, the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) introduced the Prime Time Access Rule, which freed local network affiliates in the top 50 markets (in practice, the entire network) to take a half-hour of prime time from the networks on Mondays through Saturdays and one full hour on Sundays.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] After a six-month hiatus in late 1971, CBS found a prime place for *60 Minutes* in a portion of that displaced time, 6:00 p.m. to 7:00 p.m.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Central Time) on Sundays in January 1972.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] This proved somewhat less than satisfactory, however, because in order to accommodate CBS telecasts of late afternoon National Football League (NFL) games, *60 Minutes* went on hiatus during the fall from 1972 to 1975 (and the summer of 1972).
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] This took place because football telecasts were protected contractually from interruptions in the wake of the infamous "Heidi Bowl" incident on NBC in November 1968.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Eventually, during the summers of 1973 through 1975, CBS did allow the program back onto the prime time schedule proper, on Fridays in 1973 and Sundays the two years thereafter, as a replacement for programs aired during the regular television season.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] It was only when the FCC returned an hour to the networks on Sundays (for news or family programming), which had been taken away from them four years earlier, in a 1975 amendment to the Access Rule, that CBS finally found a viable permanent timeslot for *60 Minutes*.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] When the family-oriented drama *Three for the Road* ended after a 12-week run in the fall, the news magazine took its place at 7:00 p.m.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] This move, and the addition of then-White House correspondent Dan Rather to the reporting team, made the program into a strong ratings hit and, eventually, a general cultural phenomenon.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] This was no less than a stunning reversal of the historically poor ratings performances of documentary programs on network television.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] By 1976, *60 Minutes* became the top-rated program on Sunday nights in the US.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] By 1979, it had achieved the #1 spot among all television programs in the Nielsen ratings, unheard of before for a news broadcast in prime time.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] This success translated into great profits for CBS; advertising rates increased from $17,000 per 30-second spot in 1975 to $175,000 in 1982.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The program sometimes does not start until after 7:00 p.m.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Eastern, due largely to CBS Sports live sporting events.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] At the conclusion of an NFL game, *60 Minutes* will air in its entirety and delay all subsequent programs.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] However, in the Pacific time zone, *60 Minutes* is always able to start at its scheduled time as live sports coverage ends earlier in the afternoon.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Starting in the 2012–2013 season, in order to accommodate a new NFL scheduling policy that the second game of a doubleheader start at 4:25 p.m., CBS changed the scheduled start time of *60 Minutes* to 7:30 p.m.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Eastern time (or game conclusion) for Eastern and Central Time Zone stations which are receiving a game in that window.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Eastern/Pacific (or game conclusion if a late single game is airing in the eastern markets) on stations which are not broadcasting a late game in a given week (or for Western time zones even if a doubleheader airs).
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Since the 2023–2024 season, the show began to have occasional 90-minute episodes.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] For most of the 1970s, the program included *Point/Counterpoint*, in which a liberal and conservative commentator debated an issue.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] This segment originally featured James J.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Kilpatrick representing the conservative side and Nicholas von Hoffman for the liberal, with Shana Alexander taking over for von Hoffman after he departed in 1974.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The segment was an innovation that caught the public imagination as live versions of competing editorials.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] In 1979, Alexander asked Hewitt to raise the $350 per week pay; Hewitt declined, and the segment ended.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] A similar concept was revived briefly in March 2003 featuring Bob Dole and Bill Clinton, former opponents in the 1996 presidential election.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The pair agreed to do ten segments (titled *Clinton/Dole* and *Dole/Clinton* in alternating weeks), but these did not continue into the 2003–2004 fall season.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Reports indicated that the segments were considered too gentlemanly, in the style of the earlier *Point/Counterpoint*, and lacked the feistiness of *Crossfire*.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] From 1978 to 2011, the program usually ended with (usually light-hearted and humorous) commentary by Andy Rooney expounding on topics of wildly varying importance, ranging from international politics, to economics, and his personal philosophy on everyday life.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] One recurring topic was measuring the amount of coffee in coffee cans.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Rooney's pieces, particularly one in which he referred to actor Mel Gibson as a "wacko", on occasion led to complaints from viewers.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] After four weeks without Rooney, *60 Minutes* lost 20% of its audience.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] CBS management concluded that it was in their best interest to have Rooney return immediately.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Rooney published several books documenting his contributions to the program, including *Years of Minutes* and *A Few Minutes with Andy Rooney*.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Rooney retired from *60 Minutes*, delivering his final commentary on October 2, 2011; it was his 1,097th commentary over his 34-year career on the program.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] He died one month later on November 4, 2011.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On November 13, 2011, *60 Minutes* featured an hour-long tribute to Rooney and his career and included a rebroadcast of his final commentary segment.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The opening sequence features a *60 Minutes* "magazine cover" with the show's trademark, an Aristo stopwatch, intercut with preview clips of the episode's stories.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The sequence ends with each of the correspondents and hosts introducing themselves.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The last host who appears then says, "Those stories tonight on *60 Minutes*".
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] When Rooney was a prominent fixture, the final line was "Those stories and Andy Rooney, tonight on *60 Minutes*".
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Before that, and whenever Rooney did not appear, the final line was "Those stories and more, tonight on *60 Minutes*".
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The stopwatch counts off each of the broadcast's 60 minutes, starting from zero at the beginning of each show.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] It is seen during the opening title sequence, before each commercial break, and at the tail-end of the closing credits, and each time it appears it displays (within reasonable accuracy) the elapsed time of the episode to that point.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On October 29, 2006, the opening sequence changed from a black background, which had been used for over a decade, to white.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Also, the gray background for the Aristo stopwatch in the "cover" changed to red, the color for the title text changed to white, and the stopwatch itself changed from the diagonal position it had been oriented in for 31 years to an upright position.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Videos and transcripts of *60 Minutes* editions, as well as clips that were not included in the broadcast are available on the program's website.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] In September 2010, the program launched a website called "60 Minutes Overtime", in which stories broadcast on-air are discussed in further detail.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Previously the show had a partnership with Yahoo! for distribution of extra content.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Based on viewership ratings, *60 Minutes* is the most successful program in American television history since it was moved into its present timeslot in 1975.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] *60 Minutes* was a top ten show for 23 seasons in a row (1977–2000), an unsurpassed record, and has made the Top 20 for every season since the 1976–1977 season, except from 2005 to 2008.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On November 16, 2008, the edition featuring an interview with President-elect Barack Obama, earned a total viewership of 25.1 million viewers.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On October 6, 2013, the broadcast (which was delayed by 44 minutes that evening due to a Denver Broncos–Dallas Cowboys NFL game) drew 17.94 million viewers; retaining 63% of the 28.32 million viewers of its lead-in, and making it the most watched *60 Minutes* broadcast since December 16, 2012.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On December 1, 2013, the broadcast (delayed 50 minutes due to a Broncos–Kansas City Chiefs game) was watched by 18.09 million viewers, retaining 66% of its NFL lead-in (which earned 28.11 million viewers during the 7:00 p.m. hour).
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On March 25, 2018, the edition featuring Stormy Daniels giving details on her alleged affair with President Donald Trump drew 22.1 million viewers, the most since the 2008 Obama interview.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The broadcast was delayed due to the NCAA men's basketball regional final on CBS between Kansas and Duke going to overtime.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] As of June 26, 2017, *60 Minutes* had won a total of 138 Emmy Awards, a record for American primetime programs.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The show received an Investigative Reporter and Editor medal for their segment "The Osprey", documenting a Marine cover-up of deadly flaws in the V-22 Osprey aircraft.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] In 1983, a report by Morley Safer, "Lenell Geter's in Jail", helped exonerate a Texas man who was wrongly convicted and imprisoned for armed robbery.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] As of 2021, *60 Minutes* is the longest continuously running program of any genre scheduled during American network prime time.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Eastern Time on Sundays since December 7, 1975 (although since 2012, it moves to 7:30 p.m.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Eastern Time on Sundays if CBS has a late NFL game).
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The show has been praised for landmark journalism and received many awards.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On November 23, 1986, *60 Minutes* aired a segment greenlit by Hewitt, concerning the Audi 5000 automobile, a popular German luxury car.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The story covered a supposed problem of "unintended acceleration" when the brake pedal was pushed, with emotional interviews with six people who sued Audi (unsuccessfully) after they crashed their cars, including one woman whose six-year-old son had been killed.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] In the *60 Minutes* segment footage was shown of an Audi 5000 with the accelerator "moving down on its own", accelerating the car.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] It later emerged that an expert witness employed by one of the plaintiffs modified the accelerator with a concealed device, causing the "unintended acceleration".
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Independent investigators concluded that this "unintended acceleration" was most likely due to driver error, where the driver let their foot slip off the brake and onto the accelerator.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Tests by Audi and independent journalists showed that even with the throttle wide open, the car would simply stall if the brakes were actually being used.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The incident devastated Audi sales in the United States, which did not rebound for 15 years.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The initial incidents which prompted the report were found by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration and Transport Canada to have been attributable to operator error, where car owners had depressed the accelerator pedal instead of the brake pedal.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] CBS issued a partial retraction, without acknowledging the test results of involved government agencies.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Years later, *Dateline NBC*, a rival to *60 Minutes*, was found guilty of similar tactics regarding the fuel tank integrity of General Motors pickup trucks.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] A segment aired in December, 1980, concerning the alleged Jeep CJ-5 *high rollover risk* as demonstrated in Insurance Institute for Highway Safety testing.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The demonstration was a Jeep rolling over during an extreme turn at 20 mph (32 km/h), something that would not cause other cars to roll over.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] It was deemed by *60 Minutes* reporters as the "most dangerous thing on four wheels".
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] After the show aired, many people were concerned about the safety of the vehicle, and following sales plummeted.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] This tarnished the reputation of the Jeep CJ; the model was discontinued in 1986.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Years after the incident occurred, it was found that the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety had attempted to roll the car 435 times, only having 8 rollovers.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The show had also failed to mention/show that there were weights hanging on spots of the vehicle that had caused the vehicle to have a higher rollover risk.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] In February 1989, *60 Minutes* aired a report by the Natural Resources Defense Council claiming that the use of daminozide (Alar) on apples presented an unacceptably high health risk to consumers.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Apple sales dropped and CBS was sued unsuccessfully by apple growers.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Alar was subsequently banned for use on food crops in the U.S. by the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA).
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On March 3, 1991, *60 Minutes* broadcast "Werner Erhard," which dealt with controversies involving Erhard's personal and business life.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] A year after the *60 Minutes* piece aired, Erhard filed a lawsuit against CBS, claiming that the broadcast contained several "false, misleading and defamatory" statements about him.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] One month after filing the lawsuit, Erhard filed for dismissal.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Erhard later told Larry King in an interview that he dropped the suit after receiving legal advice telling him that in order to win it, he had to prove not only that CBS knew the allegations were false but also that CBS acted with malice.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] In 1995, former Brown & Williamson Vice President for Research and Development Jeffrey Wigand provided information to *60 Minutes* producer Lowell Bergman pertaining to B&W having systematically hidden the health risks of their cigarettes .
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Furthermore, it was alleged that B&W had introduced foreign agents (such as fiberglass and ammonia) with the intent of enhancing the effect of nicotine.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Bergman began to produce a piece based upon the information, but ran into opposition from Don Hewitt who, along with CBS lawyers, feared a billion-dollar lawsuit from Brown and Williamson for tortious interference for encouraging Wigand to violate his non-disclosure agreement.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] A number of people at CBS would benefit from a sale of CBS to Westinghouse Electric Corporation, including the head of CBS lawyers and CBS News.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Also, because of the interview, the son of CBS President Laurence Tisch (who also controlled Lorillard Tobacco) was among the people from the big tobacco companies at risk of being caught having committed perjury.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Due to Hewitt's hesitation, *The Wall Street Journal* instead broke Wigand's story.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The *60 Minutes* piece was eventually aired with substantially altered content and minus some of the most damning evidence against B&W.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The exposé of the incident was published in an article in *Vanity Fair* by Marie Brenner, entitled "The Man Who Knew Too Much".
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] In 1997, *60 Minutes* alleged that agents of the U.S.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Customs Service ignored drug trafficking across the Mexico–United States border at San Diego.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The only evidence was a memorandum apparently written by Rudy Camacho, who was the head of the San Diego branch office.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Based on this memo, CBS alleged that Camacho had allowed trucks belonging to a particular firm to cross the border unimpeded.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Mike Horner, a former Customs Service employee, had passed the memos on to *60 Minutes*, and even provided a copy with an official stamp.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Camacho was not consulted about the piece, and his career was devastated in the immediate term as his own department placed suspicion on him.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] In the end, it turned out that Horner had forged the documents as an act of revenge for his treatment within the Customs Service.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Camacho sued CBS and settled for an undisclosed amount of money in damages.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] *60 Minutes* founder Don Hewitt was forced to issue an on-air retraction.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] A legal battle between archaeologists and the Umatilla tribe over the remains of a skeleton, nicknamed Kennewick Man, was reported by *60 Minutes* on October 25, 1998, to which the Umatilla tribe reacted negatively.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The tribe considered the segment heavily biased in favor of the scientists, cutting out important arguments, such as explanations of the Native American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The report focused heavily on the racial politics of the controversy and also added inflammatory arguments, such as questioning the legitimacy of Native American sovereignty—much of the racial focus of the segment was later reported to have been either unfounded and/or misinterpreted.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On March 12, 2000, *60 Minutes* aired an interview with Oklahoma City bomber Timothy McVeigh.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] At the time, McVeigh had already been convicted and sentenced to death for the bombing of the Alfred P.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Murrah Federal Building in April 1995, and the subsequent deaths of 168 people.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On the program, McVeigh was given the opportunity to vent against the government.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Following the program, a federal policy called the Special Confinement Unit Media Policy was enacted prohibiting face-to-face interviews with death row inmates.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] A federal inmate challenged the policy in *Hammer v.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit upheld the prison policy.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] In March 2010, the United States Supreme Court declined to hear an appeal in the case, and the policy limiting media access to death row inmates remains in place.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] CBS refuses to show the entire interview, and has stated no reasons.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The Killian documents controversy involved six documents critical of George W.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Bush's service in the Texas Air National Guard from 1972-73.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Four of these documents were presented as authentic in a *60 Minutes II* episode aired on September 8, 2004, less than two months before the 2004 presidential election, but it was later found that CBS had failed to authenticate the documents.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Subsequently, several typewriter and typography experts concluded the documents are forgeries, as have some media sources.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] No forensic document examiners or typography experts authenticated the documents, which may not be possible without original documents.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Bill Burkett, claimed to have burned the originals after faxing copies to CBS.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The incident was dramatized for the feature-length film, *Truth*.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On March 29, 2009, a segment titled "The Internet Is Infected" aired on *60 Minutes*, which featured an interview with Don Jackson, a data protection professional for SecureWorks.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Jackson himself declared in the program that "a part of [his] job is to know the enemy".
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] However, during the interview, Jackson showed a photo of Finnish upper-level comprehensive school pupils and misidentified them as Russian hackers.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] In the photo, one of the children wears a jacket with the coat of arms of Finland on it.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Another one wears a cap which clearly has the logo of Karjala, a Finnish brand of beer, on it.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The principal of the school in Taivalkoski confirmed that the photo was taken at the school about five years before the program was broadcast.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The photo's exact origins are unknown, but it is widely known in Finland, having been originally posted to the Finnish social networking site IRC-Galleria in the early 2000s.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] It spread all over Finnish internet communities, and even originated a couple of patriotically titled (but intentionally misspelled) mock sites.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] *60 Minutes* later issued a correction and on-air apology.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] He also claimed to have visited a Benghazi hospital earlier that night where he saw Ambassador Christopher Stevens' body.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] In the days following the report, Davies' personal actions were challenged.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The FBI, which had interviewed Davies several times and considered him a credible source, said the account Davies had given them was different from what he told *60 Minutes*.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Davies stood by his story, but the inconsistency ultimately prompted *60 Minutes* to conclude it was a mistake to include Davies in their report.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] After the correction, a journalistic review was conducted by Al Ortiz, CBS News' executive director of standards and practices.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Ortiz determined that red flags about Davies' account were missed.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Davies had told the program and written in his book that he told an alternative version of his actions to his employer, who he said had demanded that he stay inside his Benghazi villa as the attack unfolded.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] That alternative version was shared with U.S. authorities; *60 Minutes* was unable to prove the story Davies had told them was true.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Davies' book, *The Embassy House*, was published two days after the *60 Minutes* report, by Threshold Editions, part of the Simon and Schuster unit of CBS.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] It was pulled from shelves once *60 Minutes* issued its correction.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On November 26, 2013, Logan was forced to take a leave of absence due to the errors in the Benghazi report.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On December 15, 2013, *60 Minutes* aired a report on the workings of the National Security Agency (NSA) that was widely criticized as misleading and a biased "puff piece".
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Complaints included that the Agency's perspective was presented unchallenged and that privacy campaigners were not invited to present the counter-arguments to the Agency's claims.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] These claims included NSA denials of "potentially extralegal" data collection.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The story was reported by John Miller, who once worked in the office of the Director of National Intelligence.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On March 30, 2014, *60 Minutes* presented a story on the Tesla Model S luxury electric automobile, with Scott Pelley conducting an interview with CEO Elon Musk concerning the car brand as well as his company SpaceX.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Within a day, the automotive blog site Jalopnik reported that the sounds accompanying footage of the car shown during the story were actually sounds from a traditional gasoline engine dubbed over the footage, when in reality the electric car makes no such sounds.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] CBS released a statement explaining that the sound was the result of an audio editing error, and subsequently removed the sound from the online version of the piece.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] However, several news outlets, as well as Jalopnik itself, expressed doubt over the authenticity of this explanation, noting the similar scandal involving Tesla Motors and the *New York Times* in 2013.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] After the resignation of CBS news head Les Moonves, an investigation into sexual harassment at CBS, including *60 Minutes*, uncovered evidence of long-running sexual harassment issues stemming from behavior of producers Jeff Fager and Don Hewitt.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Subsequently, Palm Beach County Mayor Dave Kerner accused *60 Minutes* of reporting "intentionally false" information, while Karol Markowicz of the *New York Post* characterized Alfonsi as coming off as a "political activist" in the segment.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] A spokesperson for *60 Minutes* defended the story for having included DeSantis' response to the accusation.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] PolitiFact stated that by omitting DeSantis' remarks on why the state partnered with Publix to distribute vaccines, the clip could be considered to be "deceptive editing".
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On May 16, 2021, Anderson Cooper's story in *60 Minutes* on the flaws in facial recognition technology used by the police resulting in incorrect identification of people of color received backlash for denying credit to the black female researchers who pioneered the field.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The segment was criticized by the Algorithmic Justice League for "deliberately excluding the groundbreaking and award-winning work of prominent black women AI researchers Joy Buolamwini, Dr.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Timnit Gebru, and Inioluwa Deborah Raji".
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The segment was called out for its hypocrisy for failing to credit black women for their pioneering work in a segment highlighting how facial recognition software often leaves out black, Asian, and female faces.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] CBS later issued a statement explaining that these researchers were not included due to time restrictions of the segment.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On December 7, 2024, Donald Trump filed a $20 billion lawsuit against CBS and its parent company, Paramount Global, alleging that the network deceptively edited an interview with Vice President Kamala Harris on *60 Minutes* to sway public opinion in her favor.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] The lawsuit, submitted in the lead-up to the 2024 presidential election, claims that the editing distorted Harris's response regarding Middle East policy.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Both parties agreed to enter mediation, coinciding with a planned $8 billion merger between Paramount and Skydance, which requires approval from the Federal Communications Commission (FCC).
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Within Paramount, there was reportedly internal disagreement over whether to settle the dispute, as the producers of *60 Minutes* maintained their conduct was appropriate and opposed offering an apology.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] In early April 2025, Trump expressed his "hope" that the FCC would punish CBS for running on *60 Minutes* stories on Ukraine and Greenland that he disapproved of.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Trump filed a lawsuit in Texas accusing CBS of violating the state's Deceptive Trade Practices Act, a consumer protection law.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On April 22, 2025, Bill Owens resigned as the show's executive producer, telling staff he believed he no longer had journalistic independence.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] He said in a memo that the show would continue to cover the second Trump administration the same way it has covered others.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] In the "Last Minute" segment of the show on April 27, 2025, Scott Pelley praised Owens for ensuring that the types of controversial stories the show had covered since its creation, most recently the Gaza war and the Trump administration, were covered fairly.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On May 19, 2025, CBS News chief executive Wendy McMahon followed Bill Owens in resigning.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] McMahon explained in a memo to staff, “The past few months have been challenging.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On July 2, 2025, Paramount agreed to a $16 million settlement.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] As part of the deal, the company did not apologize or admit wrongdoing, agreed to release full transcripts of interviews with future U.S. presidential candidates after they air, and stated that the funds will go to Trump's future presidential library.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On the July 14, 2025, episode of CBS's late-night talk show *The Late Show with Stephen Colbert*, host Stephen Colbert called the settlement a "big fat bribe".
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Three days later, CBS announced that it would not renew Colbert's contract with the network, and that it would end the *Late Show* franchise at the conclusion of the 2025–26 television season.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Although CBS claimed that the decision to end the show was "purely" financial, it was suspected that the decision may have been politically-motivated due to Colbert's comments and regular history of satirizing the Trump administration.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On December 21, 2025, CBS News abruptly pulled a planned segment on El Salvador's Terrorism Confinement Center (CECOT) and President Trump's deportation of Venezuelan migrants from that night's episode, and announced that it would be postponed to a future date.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Correspondent Sharyn Alfonsi accused Bari Weiss—who had recently been named editor-in-chief of CBS News—of intervening for political reasons, despite the segment having been cleared by the network's staff.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On December 22, Canadian broadcaster Global accidentally made the original cut of the episode containing the CECOT story available on its video on demand platform, causing it to be widely disseminated online.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Alfonsi stated in a email memorandum to colleagues that the production team did request comments and interviews from White House officials, the State Department, and the Department of Homeland Security, which were all refused.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] On January 18, 2026, the segment aired alongside a piece on the relations between Minneapolis citizens and ICE officers after the death of Renée Good.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] Correspondent Scott Pelley was fired in June 2026.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p01] He complained about management, including CBS News Chief Bari Weiss, and the incoming executive-producer of the show, Nick Bilton.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] The main *60 Minutes* show has created a number of spin-offs over the years.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] In September 2004, the program was marred by controversy when it aired a report alleging that presidential candidate George W.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] Bush had previously been suspended from the Texas Air National Guard as unfit for duty; the claims were found to have been based on falsified documents received by the show's staff.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] The show later moved to Friday nights in July 2005 (rebranding back to *60 Minutes II*), and aired its final episode on September 2, 2005.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] In 2011, CNBC began airing a *60 Minutes* spin-off of its own, called *60 Minutes on CNBC*.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] Hosted by Lesley Stahl and Steve Kroft, it aired updated business-related reports seen on the original broadcasts and offers footage that was not included when the segments first aired.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] In 2013, CBS's sister premium television network Showtime premiered *60 Minutes Sports*, a monthly spin-off focused on sports-related stories and classic interviews from the show's archives.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] Personalities from CBS Sports also contributed to the program; correspondents included Sharyn Alfonsi and Armen Keteyian.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] The spin-off was considered a competitor to HBO's *Real Sports*.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] In June 2020, the show launched *60 in 6* on Quibi, featuring original weekly 6-minute programs.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] Correspondents were Enrique Acevedo, Seth Doane, Wesley Lowery, and Laurie Segall.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] It was originally set to launch in April 2020.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] On the June 21, 2020, broadcast of *60 in 6*, Doane covered the show's exposure to COVID-19 in a piece titled "CBS News Battles COVID-19".
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] The piece revealed that CBS News had flown in staffers, including from Seattle and Rome, in early March 2020 to begin filming promotional material for *60 in 6*.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] This brought COVID-19-positive people in close contact with CBS employees; as a result, CBS Broadcast Center and several other buildings in Manhattan were temporarily closed.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] Quibi went bankrupt in December 2020 and the program concluded with it.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] In March 2021, Paramount+ premiered *60 Minutes+*, a weekly spin-off aimed at a younger audience.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] The correspondents from *60 in 6* returned for this spin-off, as well as producer Jonathan Blakely.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] In January 2022, the show was cancelled after 30 episodes.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] For the *60 Minutes* 25th anniversary program in 1993, Charles Kuralt revisited notable stories and celebrity appearances and also interviewed Don Hewitt and correspondents, both the active and some former ones.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] The Australian version of *60 Minutes* premiered on February 11, 1979.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] It still airs each Sunday night at 7:30 p.m. on the Nine Network and affiliates.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] Although Nine Network has the rights to the format, as of 2007, it does not have rights to stories from the American program, which is owned by competitor 10 News Australia after Network Ten's acquisition by CBS in 2017.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] Nevertheless, stories from the flagship *60 Minutes* program in the U.S. often air on the Australian program by subleasing them from Ten.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] In 1981, *60 Minutes* won a Logie Award for their investigation of lethal abuses at the Chelmsford psychiatric hospital in Sydney.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] In the mid-1980s, an edited version (approx.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] This version retained the English-language track of the original but also featured German dubbing.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] The New Zealand version of *60 Minutes* has aired on national television since 1989, when it was originally launched on TV3.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] In 1992, the rights were acquired by TVNZ, who began broadcasting it in 1993.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] The network aired the program for nine years before dropping it in 2002 for its own program, entitled *Sunday*, which is currently the highest-rated current affairs show broadcast on New Zealand television, followed by *20/20*.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] *60 Minutes* was broadcast by rival network TV3, before switching to the Sky Television owned Prime channel in 2013, when the contract changed hands.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] In 1992, the GNT channel brought its original version with dubbed subtitles from that country.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] And later, in 2004, Rede Bandeirantes, planned a licensed localized version, but the plan was cancelled.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] And even so that year, it returned as a frame, i.e. a rubric in the program *Domingo Espetacular* on Rede Record, a competitor of Rede Globo's program *Fantástico*.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] SIC Notícias acquired the broadcasting rights to the program in 2001.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] The original episodes were shown in Portugal with introductory and final comments by journalist Mário Crespo, who conducted the program until 2014.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] It is presently hosted by anchors of the aforementioned network on a rotational basis, who eventually adopted the previous model.
[src:adx-florence/60-minutes-p02] The news program of National Broadcasting of Chile (TVN), the public television network in that country, was named *60 Minutos* ("60 Minutes") from 1975 to 1988, but the program had no association with the American version and no investigative reporting.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The **United States Penitentiary, Administrative Maximum Facility** (abbreviated as **USP Florence ADMAX**; commonly known as **ADX Florence**, **Florence Supermax**, and the **Alcatraz of the Rockies**) is a United States federal prison for men in Fremont County, Colorado, United States.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] It is operated by the Federal Bureau of Prisons, a division of the United States Department of Justice.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The prison houses some of the most dangerous criminals in the United States.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] ADX Florence, constructed in 1994 and opened the following year, is classed as a supermax or "control unit" prison, that provides a higher, more controlled level of custody than a regular maximum security prison (or "high security", as it is called in the federal prison system).
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] ADX Florence forms part of the Federal Correctional Complex, Florence (FCC Florence), which is situated on 49 acres (20 hectares) of land and houses different facilities with varying degrees of security, including the adjacent United States Penitentiary, Florence High.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The inmates are confined for most of the day in single cells with facilities made of poured, reinforced concrete to deter self-harm, and are under 24-hour supervision, carried out intensively with high staff–inmate ratios.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The institution is unofficially known as ADX Florence or "the Alcatraz of the Rockies".
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] It is part of the Federal Correctional Complex, Florence, run by the Federal Bureau of Prisons under the United States Department of Justice.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The complex includes a minimum-security camp that, as of February 2019, held more prisoners than the supermax unit.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The number of inmates has declined, and as of 2021, two housing units had closed due to low population.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Florence houses male inmates in the federal prison system deemed the most dangerous and in need of the tightest control, including prisoners whose escape would pose a serious threat to national security.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Women classified as a "special management concern" due to violence or escape attempts are confined at Federal Medical Center, Carswell, in Fort Worth, Texas.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] On October 22, 1983, Thomas Silverstein and Clayton Fountain, members of the Aryan Brotherhood, fatally stabbed correctional officers Merle Clutts and Robert Hoffman at the United States Penitentiary, Marion.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The stabbings took place only a few hours apart and were blamed on inadequate prison design.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Federal Bureau of Prisons director Norman Carlson proposed a new facility to isolate the most dangerous, uncontrollable inmates for security and safety.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Under his leadership, USP Marion was operated in permanent lockdown for 23 years, serving as a model for ADX as a control unit prison.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Carlson believed that the prison would hold criminals who were desperate enough to murder corrections officers or other inmates in the hopes of being sentenced to death.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] He argued that as draconian as these measures were, they were the only way to deal with inmates who have "absolutely no concern for human life".
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The county already had nine prisons, but the lure of 750 to 900 permanent jobs (plus temporary jobs during the prison's construction) led residents to raise $160,000 to purchase 600 acres (240 ha) for the new prison.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Hundreds of people attended the groundbreaking for the facility, which was designed by two architecture firms in Colorado Springs and cost $60 million to build.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The supermax unit at Florence houses 408 male inmates as of April 2026, each assigned to one of six security levels.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] It is designed to house up to 474 inmates but has never been at full capacity.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The facility is best known for housing inmates who have been deemed too dangerous, too high-profile, or too great a security risk for even maximum-security prisons.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] For example, Joseph Romano was sentenced to life in federal prison for plotting to murder the judge and federal prosecutor who helped sentence him to 15 years in prison for masterminding a coin fraud operation.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] While in prison, he plotted to murder an undercover officer who had taken part in the investigation.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] When this came to light, Romano was transferred to Florence.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Another notable inmate was Robert Hanssen, who spied for the Soviet Union and Russia on and off from 1978 until his arrest in 2001.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Hanssen served a life sentence there and died in 2023.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The majority of current inmates, however, have an extensive history of committing violent crimes in other prisons, including murder, against corrections officers and fellow inmates.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] These inmates are kept in administrative segregation; they are kept in solitary confinement for 23 hours a day.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] During their hour outside the cell, which can occur at any time of day or night, they are kept under restraint (handcuffed, shackled, or both).
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The hour outside of the cell is for exercise and a phone call if they have earned the privilege.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Their diet is restricted to ensure that the food cannot be used to harm themselves or to create unhygienic conditions in their cell.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Some cells have showers, which are run on a timer to prevent flooding, further reducing the amount of handling of inmates that correctional officers have to perform.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] After at least one year, depending on their conduct, inmates are gradually allowed out for longer periods.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The long-term goal is to keep them at Florence for no more than three years and then to transfer them to a less restrictive prison to serve the remainder of their sentences.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] According to a 1998 report in the *San Francisco Chronicle*, Florence's main purpose is to "try and extract reasonably peaceful behavior from extremely violent career prisoners".
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] One cell block at Florence was once known as "Bombers Row" because a number of particularly notable terrorists, including notable domestic terrorists, were held there: Timothy McVeigh, Ramzi Yousef, Ted Kaczynski, Eric Rudolph, and Dzhokhar Tsarnaev.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] ADX Florence is a 37-acre (15 ha) complex located at 5880 Highway 67, in an unincorporated area, with a Florence, Colorado, postal address.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] It is located about 100 miles (160 km) south of Denver and 40 miles (64 km) south of Colorado Springs.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] It is part of the Federal Correctional Complex, Florence (FCC Florence) which consists of three correctional facilities, each with a different security rating.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The majority of the facility is above ground, with the exception of a subterranean corridor that links cellblocks to the lobby.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Each cell contains a desk, stool, and bed, constructed almost entirely of poured concrete, as well as a toilet that shuts off if blocked, a shower that runs on a timer to prevent flooding, and a sink lacking a potentially dangerous tap.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The 4-inch-by-4-foot (10 cm × 1.2 m) windows are designed to prevent inmates from knowing their specific location within the complex.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] They can see only the sky and roof through them, so it is virtually impossible to plan an escape.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Inmates exercise in a concrete pit resembling an empty swimming pool, also designed to prevent them from knowing their location in the facility.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The pit is large enough only for a prisoner to walk ten steps in a straight line or thirty-one steps in a circle.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Correctional officers generally deliver food to the cells.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Inmates transferred to Florence from other prisons may be allowed to eat in a shared dining room.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The prison as a whole contains a multitude of motion detectors, cameras, and 1,400 remote-controlled steel doors.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Officers in the prison's control center monitor inmates twenty-four hours a day and can activate a "panic button", which immediately closes every door in the facility, should an escape attempt be suspected.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Pressure pads and 12-foot (3.7 m) razor-wire fences surround the perimeter, which is patrolled by heavily armed officers.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The facility houses inmates at six differing security levels: General Population Units ("Delta", "Echo", "Fox", and "Golf" Units), the Special Housing Unit (SHU), the Special Security Unit ("H" Unit), the Control Unit, Intermediate/Transitional Units ("Kilo" and "Joker" Units), and Range 13.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Many of the security levels at ADX have special purposes or missions for the inmates who occupy them.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The Control Unit houses inmates who have committed serious conduct violations or acts of violence at other institutions.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] It also houses high-level members of organizations deemed as threats, such as prison gangs.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] "H" Unit houses inmates who are members of terror groups so designated by the Department of Justice or who have had special administrative measures (SAMs) placed on them.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Range 13 is a special four-cell wing within the Special Housing Unit for inmates in need of the tightest control.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] As of 2022, the only inmates publicly known to have been incarcerated in this unit are Ramzi Yousef and Joaquín "El Chapo" Guzmán.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The two Intermediate Units house "step-down" inmates, who can earn transfer to another institution if they remain incident-free while housed in the unit.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] This is the only unit in ADX where inmates secure themselves in their own cells, can walk freely in their range, and associate with other inmates.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] From there, inmates will typically be transferred to the supermax step-down unit in USP Florence High.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The Bureau of Prisons allowed the media to take a guided tour of Florence on September 14, 2007.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Attending reporters remarked on "an astonishing and eerie quiet" within the prison, as well as a sense of safety due to the rigorous security measures.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] *60 Minutes* producer Henry Schuster said, "A few minutes inside that cell and two hours inside Supermax were enough to remind me why I left high school a year early.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The prison has received far less criticism than comparable facilities at the state level (such as California's Pelican Bay State Prison), which tend to suffer from over-population, low staff-to-inmate ratios, and security issues.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Despite the extreme security measures to deter disruptive, violent, and dangerous behavior among inmates, there have been murders at ADX.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Silvestre Mayorqui Rivera and Richard Santiago were both charged with the first degree murder of Manuel Torres, a high-level member of the Mexican Mafia.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Left alone with no guard supervision in the prison yard on the morning of April 21, 2005, Rivera and Santiago were videotaped brutally beating and stomping Torres to death.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Rivera pleaded not guilty due to self-defense.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Prosecutors intended to seek the death penalty against Rivera and Santiago, but they were both given life sentences for the murders.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] As of 2015, both Rivera and Santiago remain at ADX.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] On April 10, 2025, U.S. attorney general Pam Bondi announced that the United States Department of Justice would seek the death penalty against ADX Florence inmate Ishmael Petty.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Petty, who was convicted of multiple robberies in Tupelo, Mississippi, in December 1997, is accused of killing fellow inmate Walter Lee Gilbert—listed by the Federal Bureau of Prisons as LaMarcus Lee Hillard—by strangulation with a bedsheet on September 19, 2020.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Petty was already serving a life sentence issued in 2002 for murdering his 71-year-old cellmate at United States Penitentiary, Pollock, and an additional 60-year sentence issued in 2015 for attacking two ADX librarians with an improvised prison shank.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Gilbert was also serving a life sentence issued by the State of Mississippi after he murdered a fellow inmate at the Mississippi State Penitentiary with a weapon fashioned from a mop.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] In 2012, eleven inmates filed a federal class-action suit against the Bureau of Prisons in *Cunningham v.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] The suit alleged chronic abuse and failure to properly diagnose prisoners who are seriously mentally ill.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] At the time of the lawsuit, at least six inmates had allegedly died by suicide; a seventh did so after the original lawsuit was filed, and an amended filing added him to the case.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Critics claim that the use of extended confinement in solitary cells severely affects prisoners' mental health, a conclusion supported by numerous studies.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] As of March 2015, settlement negotiations were underway with the help of a federal magistrate.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Some changes had by then already been made by the Bureau of Prisons.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Prisoners held in Unit H are subject to special administrative measures (SAMs) that prevent them from communicating with journalists or privately with their own lawyers or family members.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] In 2020, a British District Judge refused to extradite Julian Assange to the United States on espionage charges in part because he would possibly be subjected to solitary confinement and special administrative measures at ADX.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] On July 7, 2021, the High Court of Justice for England and Wales agreed to allow the United States to appeal this decision with the understanding that Assange "will not be subject to SAMs or imprisoned at ADX" if extradited.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] Eventually, Assange pleaded guilty to a charge under the Espionage Act of conspiracy to obtain and disclose national defense information and sentenced to 62 months' time served.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] At least nine inmates have died, or are suspected of having died, by suicide at the facility.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] In the 2011 novel *Locked On* by Tom Clancy and Mark Greaney, "The Emir" is housed in ADX Florence under the highest level of security.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] His sketches of John Clark and Domingo Chavez, smuggled out through his lawyer, Judith Cochran, play a pivotal role in the plot.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] In the 2023 fiction thriller novel *Only the Dead* by author and retired US Navy SEAL Jack Carr, protagonist James Reece is housed in Range 13 after being suspected of an assassination attempt on a fictitious characterization of the president of the United States.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] In the episode "Svengali" from *Law and Order: SVU*, criminal Robert Morten is transferred to ADX Florence after he masterminded several killings while already incarcerated at a less secure facility.
[src:adx-florence/adx-florence] In the series finale of *Better Call Saul*, the title character Jimmy McGill (Saul Goodman) is sentenced to 86 years at a fictionalized version of ADX Florence called ADX Montrose.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama is nicknamed the *Yellowhammer State*, after the state bird.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama is also known as the "Heart of Dixie" and the "Cotton State".
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The state has diverse geography, with the north dominated by the mountainous Tennessee Valley and the south by Mobile Bay.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama's capital is Montgomery, and its largest city by population and area is Huntsville.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Its oldest city is Mobile, founded by French colonists (Alabama Creoles) in 1702 as the capital of French Louisiana.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Greater Birmingham is Alabama's largest metropolitan area and its economic center.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Politically, as part of the Deep South, or "Bible Belt", Alabama is a predominantly conservative state and is known for its Southern culture.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Within Alabama, American football, particularly at the college level, is part of the state's culture.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Originally the area of Alabama was home to many native tribes.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] It was a Spanish territory from the sixteenth century until the French acquired it in the early eighteenth century.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The British won the territory in 1763 until losing it in the American Revolutionary War.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Spain held Mobile as part of Spanish West Florida until 1813.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In December 1819, Alabama was recognized as a state.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] During the antebellum period, Alabama was a major producer of cotton and widely used African American slave labor.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In 1861, the state seceded from the United States to become part of the Confederate States of America, with Montgomery acting as its first capital.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Following the American Civil War, it would suffer decades of economic hardship, in part due to agriculture and a few cash crops being the main driver of the state's economy.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Similar to other former slave states, Alabamian legislators employed Jim Crow laws from the late 19th century until the 1960s.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] High-profile events such as the Selma to Montgomery marches made the state a focal point of the civil rights movement in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] During and after World War II, the state's economy diversified with new industries.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In 1960, the establishment of NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville helped boost Alabama's economic growth by developing a local aerospace industry.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama's economy in the 21st century is based on automotive, finance, tourism, manufacturing, aerospace, mineral extraction, healthcare, education, retail, and technology.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Despite the economic and industrial growth in recent decades, Alabama typically ranks low in terms of health outcomes, educational attainment, and median household income.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The name of the Alabama River and state is derived from the Alabama people, a Muskogean-speaking tribe whose members lived just below the confluence of the Coosa and Tallapoosa rivers on the upper reaches of the river.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In the Alabama language, the word for a person of Alabama lineage is *Albaamo* (or variously *Albaama* or *Albàamo* in different dialects; the plural form is *Albaamaha*).
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The word's spelling varies significantly among historical sources.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The first usage appears in three accounts of the Hernando de Soto expedition of 1540: Garcilaso de la Vega used *Alibamo*, while the Knight of Elvas and Rodrigo Ranjel wrote *Alibamu* and *Limamu*, respectively, in transliterations of the term.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] As early as 1702, the French called the tribe the *Alibamon*, with French maps identifying the river as *Rivière des Alibamons*.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Other spellings of the name have included *Alibamu*, *Alabamo*, *Albama*, *Alebamon*, *Alibama*, *Alibamou*, *Alabamu*, and *Allibamou*.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The use of state names derived from Native American languages is common in the U.S.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] An estimated 26 states have names of Native American origin.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Some scholars suggest the word comes from the Choctaw *alba* (meaning 'plants' or 'weeds') and *amo* (meaning 'to cut', 'to trim', or 'to gather').
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The meaning may have been 'clearers of the thicket' or 'herb gatherers', referring to clearing land for cultivation or collecting medicinal plants.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The state has numerous place names of Native American origin.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] An 1842 article in the *Jacksonville Republican* proposed it meant 'Here We Rest'.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] This notion was popularized in the 1850s through the writings of Alexander Beaufort Meek.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Experts in the Muskogean languages have not found any evidence to support such a translation.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Indigenous peoples of varying cultures lived in the area for thousands of years before the advent of European colonization.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Trade with the northeastern tribes by the Ohio River began during the Burial Mound Period (1000 BC – 700 AD) and continued until European contact.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The agrarian Mississippian culture covered most of the state from 1000 to 1600 AD, with one of its major polities centered around what is now the Moundville Archaeological Site in Moundville, Alabama.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] This is the second-largest complex of the classic Middle Mississippian era, after Cahokia in present-day Illinois, which was the earliest center of the culture.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Analysis of artifacts from archaeological excavations at Moundville were the basis of scholars' formulating the characteristics of the Southeastern Ceremonial Complex (SECC).
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Contrary to popular belief, the SECC appears to have no direct links to Mesoamerican culture but developed independently.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The Ceremonial Complex represents a major component of the religion of the Mississippian peoples; it is one of the primary means by which their religion is understood.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Among the historical tribes of Native American people living in present-day Alabama at the time of European contact were the Cherokee, an Iroquoian language people; and the Muskogean-speaking Alabama (*Alibamu*), Chickasaw, Choctaw, Creek, and Koasati.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] While part of the same large language family, the Muskogee tribes developed distinct cultures and languages.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The Spanish were the first Europeans to reach Alabama during their exploration of North America in the 16th century.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The expedition of Hernando de Soto passed through Mabila and other parts of the state in 1540.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] More than 160 years later, the French founded the region's first European settlement at Old Mobile in 1702.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The city was moved to the current site of Mobile in 1711.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] This area was claimed by the French from 1702 to 1763 as part of La Louisiane.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] After the French lost to the British in the Seven Years' War, it became part of British West Florida from 1763 to 1783.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] After the U.S. victory in the American Revolutionary War, the territory was divided between the United States and Spain.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The latter retained control of this western territory from 1783 until the surrender of the Spanish garrison at Mobile to U.S. forces on April 13, 1813.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Thomas Bassett, a loyalist to the British monarchy during the Revolutionary era, was one of the earliest white settlers in the state outside Mobile.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] He settled in the Tombigbee District during the early 1770s.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The district's boundaries were roughly limited to the area within a few miles of the Tombigbee River and included portions of what is today southern Clarke County, northernmost Mobile County, and most of Washington County.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] What are now Baldwin and Mobile counties became part of Spanish West Florida in 1783, part of the independent Republic of West Florida in 1810, and finally part of the Mississippi Territory in 1812.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Most of what is now the northern two-thirds of Alabama was known as the Yazoo lands beginning during the British colonial period.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] It was claimed by the Province of Georgia from 1767 onwards.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Following the American Revolutionary War, it remained a part of Georgia, although heavily disputed.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] With the exception of the area around Mobile and the Yazoo lands, what is now the lower one-third of Alabama was made part of the Mississippi Territory when it was organized in 1798.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The Yazoo lands were added to the territory in 1804, following the Yazoo land scandal.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Spain kept a claim on its former Spanish West Florida territory in what would become the coastal counties until the Adams–Onís Treaty officially ceded it to the U.S. in 1819.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The creation of the Mississippi Territory quickly prompted debates over its division.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Amid pressure from white southerners who sought the establishment of two slave states, Congress formed the Alabama Territory from the eastern half of the Mississippi Territory on March 3, 1817.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The legislation appointed William Wyatt Bibb of Georgia as the first governor of the newly designated Alabama Territory.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Before Mississippi's admission to statehood on December 10, 1817, the more sparsely settled eastern half of the territory was separated and named the Alabama Territory.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The United States Congress created the Alabama Territory on March 3, 1817.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Stephens, now abandoned, served as the territorial capital from 1817 to 1819.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama was admitted as the 22nd state on December 14, 1819, with Congress selecting Huntsville as the site for the first Constitutional Convention.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] From July 5 to August 2, 1819, delegates met to prepare the new state constitution.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Huntsville served as temporary capital from 1819 to 1820, when the seat of government moved to Cahaba in Dallas County.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Cahaba, now a ghost town, was the first permanent state capital from 1820 to 1825.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The Alabama Fever land rush was underway when the state was admitted to the Union, with settlers and land speculators pouring into the state to take advantage of fertile land suitable for cotton cultivation.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Part of the frontier in the 1820s and 1830s, its constitution provided for universal suffrage for white men.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Southeastern planters and traders from the Upper South brought slaves with them as the cotton plantations in Alabama expanded.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The economy of the central Black Belt (named for its dark, productive soil) was built around large cotton plantations whose owners' wealth grew mainly from slave labor.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The area also drew many poor, disenfranchised people who became subsistence farmers.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama had an estimated population of under 10,000 people in 1810, but it increased to more than 300,000 people by 1830.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Most Native American tribes were completely removed from the state within a few years of the passage of the Indian Removal Act by Congress in 1830.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] From 1826 to 1846, Tuscaloosa served as Alabama's capital.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] On January 30, 1846, the Alabama legislature announced it had voted to move the capital city from Tuscaloosa to Montgomery.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The first legislative session in the new capital met in December 1847.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] A new capitol building was erected under the direction of Stephen Decatur Button of Philadelphia.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The first structure burned down in 1849, but was rebuilt on the same site in 1851.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] This second capitol building in Montgomery remains to the present day.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] It was designed by Barachias Holt of Exeter, Maine.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] By 1860, the population had increased to 964,201 people, of which nearly half, 435,080, were enslaved African Americans, and 2,690 were free people of color.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] On January 11, 1861, Alabama declared its secession from the Union.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] After remaining an independent republic for a few days, it joined the Confederate States of America.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The Confederacy's capital was initially at Montgomery.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama was heavily involved in the American Civil War.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Although comparatively few battles were fought in the state, Alabama contributed about 120,000 soldiers to the war effort.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] A company of cavalry soldiers from Huntsville, Alabama, joined Nathan Bedford Forrest's battalion in Hopkinsville, Kentucky.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The company wore new uniforms with yellow trim on the sleeves, collar and coattails.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] This led to them being greeted with "Yellowhammer", and the name later was applied to all Alabama troops in the Confederate Army.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama's slaves were freed by the 13th Amendment in 1865.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama was under military rule from the end of the war in May 1865 until its official restoration to the Union in 1868.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] From 1867 to 1874, with most white citizens barred temporarily from voting and freedmen enfranchised, many African Americans emerged as political leaders in the state.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama was represented in Congress during this period by three African-American congressmen: Jeremiah Haralson, Benjamin S.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Following the war, the state remained chiefly agricultural, with an economy tied to cotton.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] During the Reconstruction era, state legislators ratified a new state constitution in 1868 which created the state's first public school system and expanded women's rights.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Legislators funded numerous public road and railroad projects, although these were plagued with allegations of fraud and misappropriation.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Organized insurgent, resistance groups tried to suppress the freedmen and Republicans.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] These groups included The Ku Klux Klan, the Pale Faces, Knights of the White Camellia, Red Shirts, and the White League.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Reconstruction in Alabama ended in 1874, when the Democrats regained control of the legislature and governor's office through an election dominated by fraud and violence.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] They wrote another constitution in 1875, and the legislature passed the Blaine Amendment, prohibiting public money from being used to finance religiously affiliated schools.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The same year, legislation was approved that called for racially segregated schools.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Railroad passenger cars were segregated in 1891.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The 1901 constitution required racial segregation of public schools.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] By 1903 only 2,980 African Americans were registered in Alabama, although at least 74,000 were literate.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] This compared to more than 181,000 African Americans eligible to vote in 1900.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The numbers dropped even more in later decades.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The state legislature passed additional racial segregation laws related to public facilities into the 1950s: jails were segregated in 1911; hospitals in 1915; toilets, hotels, and restaurants in 1928; and bus stop waiting rooms in 1945.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] While the planter class had persuaded poor whites to vote for this legislative effort to suppress black voting, the new restrictions resulted in their disenfranchisement as well, due mostly to the imposition of a cumulative poll tax.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] By 1941, whites constituted a slight majority of those disenfranchised by these laws: 600,000 whites vs.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Nearly all blacks had lost the ability to vote.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Despite numerous legal challenges which succeeded in overturning certain provisions, the state legislature would create new ones to maintain disenfranchisement.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The exclusion of blacks from the political system persisted until after passage of federal civil rights legislation in 1965 to enforce their constitutional rights as citizens.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The rural-dominated Alabama legislature consistently underfunded schools and services for the disenfranchised African Americans, but it did not relieve them of paying taxes.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Partially as a response to chronic underfunding of education for African Americans in the South, the Rosenwald Fund began funding the construction of what came to be known as Rosenwald Schools.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In Alabama, these schools were designed, and the construction partially financed with Rosenwald funds, which paid one-third of the construction costs.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The fund required the local community and state to raise matching funds to pay the rest.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Black residents effectively taxed themselves twice, by raising additional monies to supply matching funds for such schools, which were built in many rural areas.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] They often donated land and labor as well.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Beginning in 1913, the first 80 Rosenwald Schools were built in Alabama for African American children.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] A total of 387 schools, seven teachers' houses, and several vocational buildings were completed by 1937 in the state.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Several of the surviving school buildings in the state are now listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Reflecting this emigration, the population growth rate in Alabama (see "historical populations" table below) dropped by nearly half from 1910 to 1920.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] At the same time, many rural people migrated to the city of Birmingham to work in new industrial jobs.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Birmingham experienced such rapid growth it was called the "Magic City".
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] By 1920, Birmingham was the 36th-largest city in the United States.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Heavy industry and mining were the basis of its economy.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Its residents were under-represented for decades in the state legislature, which refused to redistrict after each decennial census according to population changes, as it was required by the state constitution.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] This did not change until the late 1960s following a lawsuit and court order.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Industrial development related to the demands of World War II brought a level of prosperity to the state not seen since before the civil war.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Rural workers poured into the largest cities in the state for better jobs and a higher standard of living.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] One example of this massive influx of workers occurred in Mobile.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Between 1940 and 1943, more than 89,000 people moved into the city to work for war-related industries.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Cotton and other cash crops faded in importance as the state developed a manufacturing and service base.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Despite massive population changes in the state from 1901 to 1961, the rural-dominated legislature refused to reapportion House and Senate seats based on population, as required by the state constitution to follow the results of decennial censuses.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] They held on to old representation to maintain political and economic power in agricultural areas.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] One result was that Jefferson County, containing Birmingham's industrial and economic powerhouse, contributed more than one-third of all tax revenue to the state, but did not receive a proportional amount in services.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Urban interests were consistently underrepresented in the legislature.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In the United States Supreme Court cases of *Baker v.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Sims* (1964), the court ruled that the principle of "one man, one vote" needed to be the basis of both houses of state legislatures, and that their districts had to be based on population rather than geographic counties.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] African Americans continued to press in the 1950s and 1960s to end disenfranchisement and segregation in the state through the civil rights movement, including legal challenges.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Board of Education* that public schools had to be desegregated, but Alabama was slow to comply.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] During the 1960s, under Governor George Wallace, Alabama resisted compliance with federal demands for desegregation.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The civil rights movement had notable events in Alabama, including the Montgomery bus boycott (1955–1956), Freedom Rides in 1961, and 1965 Selma to Montgomery marches.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] These contributed to Congressional passage and enactment of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and Voting Rights Act of 1965 by the U.S.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Legal segregation ended in the states in 1964, although Jim Crow customs often continued until specifically challenged in court.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] According to *The New York Times*, by 2017, many of Alabama's African Americans were living in Alabama's cities such as Birmingham and Montgomery.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Also, the Black Belt region across central Alabama "is home to largely poor counties that are predominantly African-American.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In 1972, for the first time since 1901, the legislature completed the congressional redistricting based on the decennial census.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] This benefited the urban areas that had developed, as well as all in the population who had been underrepresented for more than sixty years.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Other changes were made to implement representative state house and senate districts.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama has made some changes since the late 20th century and has used new types of voting to increase representation.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In the 1980s, an omnibus redistricting case, *Dillard v.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Crenshaw County*, challenged the at-large voting for representative seats of 180 Alabama jurisdictions, including counties and school boards.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] At-large voting had diluted the votes of any minority in a county, as the majority tended to take all seats.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Despite African Americans making up a significant minority in the state, they had been unable to elect any representatives in most of the at-large jurisdictions.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] As part of settlement of this case, five Alabama cities and counties, including Chilton County, adopted a system of cumulative voting for election of representatives in multi-seat jurisdictions.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] This has resulted in more proportional representation for voters.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In another form of proportional representation, 23 jurisdictions use limited voting, as in Conecuh County.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In 1982, limited voting was first tested in Conecuh County.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Together use of these systems has increased the number of African Americans and women being elected to local offices, resulting in governments that are more representative of their citizens.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Beginning in the 1960s, the state's economy shifted away from its traditional lumber, steel, and textile industries because of increased foreign competition.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] However, the state, particularly Huntsville, benefited from the opening of the George C.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Marshall Space Flight Center in 1960, a major facility in the development of the Saturn rocket program and the space shuttle.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Technology and manufacturing industries, such as automobile assembly, replaced some of the state's older industries in the late twentieth century, but the state's economy and growth lagged behind other states in the area, such as Georgia and Florida.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In 2001, Alabama Supreme Court chief justice Roy Moore installed a statue of the Ten Commandments in the capitol in Montgomery.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Circuit Court ordered the statue removed, but Moore refused to follow the court order, which led to protests around the capitol in favor of keeping the monument.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The monument was removed in August 2003.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] A few natural disasters have occurred in the state in the twenty-first century.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In 2004, Hurricane Ivan, a category 3 storm upon landfall, struck the state and caused over $18 billion of damage.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] It was among the most destructive storms to strike the state in its modern history.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] A super outbreak of 62 tornadoes hit the state in April 2011 and killed 238 people, devastating many communities.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama is the thirtieth-largest state in the United States with 52,419 square miles (135,760 km2) of total area: 3.2% of the area is water, making Alabama 23rd in the amount of surface water, also giving it the second-largest inland waterway system in the United States.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] About three-fifths of the land area is part of the Gulf Coastal Plain, a gentle plain with a general descent towards the Mississippi River and the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The North Alabama region is mostly mountainous, with the Tennessee River cutting a large valley and creating numerous creeks, streams, rivers, mountains, and lakes.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama is bordered by the states of Tennessee to the north, Georgia to the east, Florida to the south, and Mississippi to the west.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama has a coastline on the Gulf of Mexico, in the extreme southern edge of the state.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The state ranges in elevation from sea level at Mobile Bay to more than 2,000 feet (610 m) in the northeast, to Mount Cheaha at 2,413 ft (735 m).
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama's land consists of 22 million acres (89,000 km2) of forest or 67% of the state's total land area.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Suburban Baldwin County, along the Gulf Coast, is the largest county in the state in both land area and water area.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Additionally, Alabama has four National Forests: Conecuh, Talladega, Tuskegee, and William B.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama also contains the Natchez Trace Parkway, the Selma To Montgomery National Historic Trail, and the Trail of Tears National Historic Trail.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] A 5-mile (8 km)-wide meteorite impact crater is located in Elmore County, just north of Montgomery.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] This is the Wetumpka crater, the site of "Alabama's greatest natural disaster".
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] A 1,000-foot (300 m)-wide meteorite hit the area about 80 million years ago.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In 2002, Christian Koeberl with the Institute of Geochemistry University of Vienna published evidence and established the site as the 157th recognized impact crater on Earth.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The state is classified as humid subtropical (*Cfa*) under the Köppen climate classification.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The average annual temperature is 64 °F (18 °C).
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Temperatures tend to be warmer in the southern part of the state with its proximity to the Gulf of Mexico, while the northern parts of the state, especially in the Appalachian Mountains in the northeast, tend to be slightly cooler.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Generally, Alabama has very hot summers and mild winters with copious precipitation throughout the year.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama receives an average of 56 inches (1,400 mm) of rainfall annually and enjoys a lengthy growing season of up to 300 days in the southern part of the state.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Summers in Alabama are among the hottest in the U.S., with high temperatures averaging over 90 °F (32 °C) throughout the summer in some parts of the state.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama is also prone to tropical storms and hurricanes.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Areas of the state far away from the Gulf are not immune to the effects of the storms, which often dump tremendous amounts of rain as they move inland and weaken.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] South Alabama reports many thunderstorms.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The Gulf Coast, around Mobile Bay, averages between 70 and 80 days per year with thunder reported.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] This activity decreases somewhat further north in the state, but even the far north of the state reports thunder on about 60 days per year.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Occasionally, thunderstorms are severe with frequent lightning and large hail; the central and northern parts of the state are most vulnerable to this type of storm.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama ranks ninth in the number of deaths from lightning and tenth in the number of deaths from lightning strikes per capita.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama, along with Oklahoma and Iowa, has the most confirmed F5 and EF5 tornadoes of any state, according to statistics from the National Climatic Data Center for the period January 1, 1950, to June 2013.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Several long-tracked F5/EF5 tornadoes have contributed to Alabama reporting more tornado fatalities since 1950 than any other state.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The state was affected by the 1974 Super Outbreak and was devastated tremendously by the 2011 Super Outbreak.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The 2011 Super Outbreak produced a record amount of tornadoes in the state.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The peak season for tornadoes varies from the northern to southern parts of the state.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama is one of the few places in the world that has a secondary tornado season in November and December besides the typically severe spring.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The northern part—along the Tennessee River Valley—is most vulnerable.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The area of Alabama and Mississippi most affected by tornadoes is sometimes referred to as Dixie Alley, as distinct from the Tornado Alley of the Southern Plains.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Winters are generally mild in Alabama, as they are throughout most of the Southeastern United States, with average January low temperatures around 40 °F (4 °C) in Mobile and around 32 °F (0 °C) in Birmingham.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Although snow is a rare event in much of Alabama, areas of the state north of Montgomery may receive a dusting of snow a few times every winter, with an occasional moderately heavy snowfall every few years.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Historic snowfall events include New Year's Eve 1963 snowstorm and the 1993 Storm of the Century.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The annual average snowfall for the Birmingham area is 2 inches (51 mm) per year.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In the southern Gulf coast, snowfall is less frequent, sometimes going several years without any snowfall.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama's highest temperature of 112 °F (44 °C) was recorded on September 5, 1925, in the unincorporated community of Centerville.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The record low of −27 °F (−33 °C) occurred on January 30, 1966, in New Market.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The state is usually ranked among the top in nation for its range of overall biodiversity.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama is in the subtropical coniferous forest biome and once boasted huge expanses of pine forest, which still form the largest proportion of forests in the state.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] It currently ranks fifth in the nation for the diversity of its flora.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] It is home to nearly 4,000 pteridophyte and spermatophyte plant species.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Indigenous animal species in the state include 62 mammal species, 93 reptile species, 73 amphibian species, roughly 307 native freshwater fish species, and 420 bird species that spend at least part of their year within the state.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Invertebrates include 97 crayfish species and 383 mollusk species.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] 113 of these mollusk species have never been collected outside the state.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] As of 2010, the state contains 461 municipalities, consisting of 174 cities and 287 towns.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Covering only 9.6% of Alabama's land mass, its municipalities are home to 60.4% of its population.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Montgomery, the state's capital, is the third-most populous settlement in Alabama; and the most populous city is Huntsville.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Census Bureau, the state contains 12 metropolitan statistical areas.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama's largest metropolitan area was Greater Birmingham.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] At the 1800 United States census, Alabama had a population of 1,250 people.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Since then, the state has continued to experience population growth with every U.S. census.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] According to the 2020 United States census the population of Alabama was 5,024,279, which represents an increase of 244,543 or 5.12%, since the 2010 census.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] This includes a natural increase since the last census of 121,054 (502,457 births minus 381,403 deaths) and an increase due to net migration of 104,991 into the state.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] According to statistics from 2012, immigration from outside the U.S. resulted in a net increase of 31,180 people, and migration within the country produced a net gain of 73,811 people.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The state had 108,000 foreign-born residents (2.4% of the state population), of which an estimated 22.2% were undocumented (24,000).
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The top countries of origin for immigrants were Mexico, China, India, Germany and Guatemala as of 2018.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] According to HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 3,752 homeless people in Alabama.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] With a population density of 99.2 people per square mile as of 2020, the majority of the state's population lives in North, Central, and South Alabama, spread throughout the Huntsville, Birmingham, Montgomery and Mobile metropolitan statistical areas.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The center of population of Alabama is located in Chilton County, outside the town of Jemison.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Many American Indian tribes such as the Cherokee, Chickasaw, Choctaw, and Coushatta inhabited present-day Alabama before European colonization.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] With Spanish, French, and British colonization of Alabama, white and black Americans migrated to the area.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] From European colonization to U.S. statehood, Alabama's population grew to become increasingly non-Hispanic white and African American.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] By the 2020 census, Alabama's total racial and ethnic population was 66.5% non-Hispanic white and 26.9% African American, with a growing Hispanic and Latino population of 5.3%.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabamians citing "American" ancestry are of overwhelmingly English extraction.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Demographers estimate that a minimum of 20–23% of people in Alabama are of predominantly English ancestry and state that the figure is probably much higher.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In the 1980 census, 1,139,976 people in Alabama cited that they were of English ancestry out of a total state population of 2,824,719 making them 41% of the state at the time and the largest ethnic group.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama has the 5th-highest black and African American population among U.S. states at 25.8% alone as of 2020.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In 2011, 46.6% of Alabama's population younger than age 1 were minorities.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The Scots-Irish were the largest non-English immigrant group from the British Isles before the American Revolution, and many settled in the South, later moving into the Deep South as it was developed.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In 1984, under the Davis–Strong Act, the state legislature established the Alabama Indian Affairs Commission.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Indigenous groups within the state had increasingly been demanding recognition as ethnic groups and seeking an end to discrimination.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Given the long history of slavery and associated racial segregation, the Native American or American Indian peoples, who have sometimes been of mixed race, have insisted on having their cultural identification respected.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In the past, their self-identification was often overlooked as the state tried to impose a binary breakdown of society into white and black.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The state has officially recognized nine American Indian tribes in the state, descended mostly from the Five Civilized Tribes of the American Southeast.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The state government has promoted recognition of American Indian contributions to the state, including the designation in 2000 for Columbus Day to be jointly celebrated as American Indian Heritage Day.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In 2020, 33,625 identified as being Native American alone, and 97,405 did in combination with one or more other races.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] According to the 2022 American Community Survey's estimates, approximately 94% of Alabamians speak English as their sole language, while 6% spoke a language other than English.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Of other languages, the majority of its multilingual population speaks Spanish (3.8%).
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In a separate 2021 study by the American University Washington College of Law, Spanish was spoken by 156,656 residents.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Following, Korean, Vietnamese, Mandarin and Cantonese, German, French, and Tagalog were the most-spoken languages; among its French-speaking population, the majority have preserved their language since French colonization.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Pre-colonial and present-day Alabamians have adhered to multiple religions including Native American and African diaspora religions, and predominantly Christianity with the establishment of Spanish missions in Florida.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Other faiths including Judaism, Islam, and Indian religions were introduced since European colonization and American settlement.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] According to a 2023 Public Religion Research Institute survey, an estimated 80% of the adult population were Christian.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In the 2008 American Religious Identification Survey, 86% of Alabama respondents reported their religion as Christian, including 6% Catholic, with 11% as having no religion.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The composition of other traditions is 0.5% Mormon, 0.5% Jewish, 0.5% Muslim, 0.5% Buddhist, and 0.5% Hindu.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama is located in the middle of the Bible Belt, a region of numerous Protestant Christians.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama has been identified as one of the most religious states in the United States, with about 58% of the population attending church regularly.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] A majority of people in the state identify as Evangelical Protestant.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] As of 2010, the three largest denominational groups in Alabama are the Southern Baptist Convention, The United Methodist Church, and non-denominational Evangelical Protestant.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In Alabama, the Southern Baptist Convention has the highest number of adherents with 1,380,121; this is followed by the United Methodist Church with 327,734 adherents, non-denominational Evangelical Protestant with 220,938 adherents, and the Catholic Church with 150,647 adherents.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Many Baptist and Methodist congregations became established in the Great Awakening of the early 19th century, when preachers proselytized across the South.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The Assemblies of God had almost 60,000 members, the Churches of Christ had nearly 120,000 members.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In a 2007 survey, nearly 70% of respondents could name all four of the Christian Gospels.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Of those who indicated a religious preference, 59% said they possessed a "full understanding" of their faith and needed no further learning.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In a 2007 poll, 92% of Alabamians reported having at least some confidence in churches in the state.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Although in much smaller numbers, many other religious faiths are represented in the state as well, including Judaism, Islam, Hinduism, Buddhism, Sikhism, the Baháʼí Faith, and Unitarian Universalism.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Jews have been present in what is now Alabama since 1763, during the colonial era of Mobile, when Sephardic Jews immigrated from London.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The oldest Jewish congregation in the state is Congregation Sha'arai Shomayim in Mobile.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] It was formally recognized by the state legislature on January 25, 1844.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Later immigrants in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries tended to be Ashkenazi Jews from eastern Europe.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Jewish denominations in the state include two Orthodox, four Conservative, ten Reform, and one Humanistic synagogue.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Muslims have been increasing in Alabama, with 31 mosques built by 2011, many by African-American converts.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] There are six Dharma centers and organizations for Theravada Buddhists.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Most monastic Buddhist temples are concentrated in southern Mobile County, near Bayou La Batre.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] This area has attracted an influx of refugees from Cambodia, Laos, and Vietnam during the 1970s and thereafter.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The four temples within a ten-mile radius of Bayou La Batre, include Chua Chanh Giac, Wat Buddharaksa, and Wat Lao Phoutthavihan.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] The first community of adherents of the Baháʼí Faith in Alabama was founded in 1896 by Paul K.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Dealy, who moved from Chicago to Fairhope.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Baháʼí centers in Alabama exist in Birmingham, Huntsville, and Florence.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] In 2018, life expectancy in Alabama was 75.1 years, below the national average of 78.7 years and is the third lowest life expectancy in the country.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Factors that can cause lower life expectancy are maternal mortality, suicide, and gun crimes.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] A Centers for Disease Control and Prevention study in 2008 showed that obesity in Alabama is a problem, with most counties having more than 29% of adults obese, except for ten which had a rate between 26% and 29%.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Residents of the state, along with those in five other states, were least likely in the nation to be physically active during leisure time.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p01] Alabama, and the southeastern U.S. in general, has one of the highest incidences of adult onset diabetes in the country, exceeding 10% of adults.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Bureau of Economic Analysis, in 2025, Alabama's total gross state product was $341.1 billion, and the state's per capita personal income was $59,677.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The state has invested in aerospace, education, health care, banking, and various heavy industries, including automobile manufacturing, mineral extraction, steel production and fabrication.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] By 2006, crop and animal production in Alabama was valued at $1.5 billion.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In contrast to the primarily agricultural economy of the previous century, this was only about one percent of the state's gross domestic product.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The number of private farms has declined at a steady rate since the 1960s, as land has been sold to developers, timber companies, and large farming conglomerates.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In 2025, 99.4% of Alabama businesses were small businesses and employed 46.0% of the state's workforce.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The state's seasonally adjusted unemployment rate was 5.8% in April 2015.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] This compared to a nationwide seasonally adjusted rate of 5.4%.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] As of May 2025, the unemployment rate was 3.3%.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama has no minimum wage and in February 2016 passed legislation preventing municipalities from setting one.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] As of 2018, Alabama has the sixth highest poverty rate among states in the U.S.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In 2017, United Nations Special Rapporteur Philip Alston toured parts of rural Alabama and observed environmental conditions that he said were poorer than anywhere he had seen in the developed world.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama's agricultural outputs include poultry and eggs, cattle, fish, plant nursery items, peanuts, cotton, grains such as corn and sorghum, vegetables, milk, soybeans, and peaches.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Although known as "The Cotton State", Alabama ranks between eighth and tenth in national cotton production, according to various reports, with Texas, Georgia and Mississippi comprising the top three.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Aquaculture is a large part of the economy of Alabama.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabamians began to practice aquaculture in the early 1960s.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] U.S. farm-raised catfish is the 8th most popular seafood product in America.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] By 2008, approximately 4,000 people in Alabama were employed by the catfish industry and Alabama produced 132 million pounds of catfish.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In 2020, Alabama produced 1⁄3 of the United States' farm-raised catfish.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The total 2020 sales of catfish raised in Alabama equaled $307 million but by 2020 the total employment of Alabamians fell to 2,442.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] From the early 2000s to 2020, the Alabamian catfish industry has declined from 250 farms and 4 processors to 66 farms and 2 processors.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Reasons for this decline include increased feed prices, catfish alternatives, COVID-19's impact on restaurant sales, disease, and fish size.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama's industrial outputs include iron and steel products (including cast-iron and steel pipe); paper, lumber, and wood products; mining (mostly coal); plastic products; cars and trucks; and apparel.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In addition, Alabama produces aerospace and electronic products, mostly in the Huntsville area, the location of NASA's George C.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Marshall Space Flight Center and the U.S.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Army Materiel Command, headquartered at Redstone Arsenal.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] A great deal of Alabama's economic growth since the 1990s has been due to the state's expanding automotive manufacturing industry.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Located in the state are Honda Manufacturing of Alabama, Hyundai Motor Manufacturing Alabama, Mercedes-Benz U.S.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] International, and Toyota Motor Manufacturing Alabama, as well as their various suppliers.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Since 1993, the automobile industry has generated more than 67,800 new jobs in the state.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama currently ranks 4th in the nation for vehicle exports.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Automakers accounted for approximately a third of the industrial expansion in the state in 2012.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The eight models produced at the state's auto factories totaled combined sales of 74,335 vehicles for 2012.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The strongest model sales during this period were the Hyundai Elantra compact car, the Mercedes-Benz GL-Class sport utility vehicle and the Honda Ridgeline sport utility truck.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Steel producers Outokumpu, Nucor, SSAB, ThyssenKrupp, and U.S.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Steel have facilities in Alabama and employ more than 10,000 people.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In May 2007, German steelmaker ThyssenKrupp selected Calvert in Mobile County for a 4.65 billion combined stainless and carbon steel processing facility.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] ThyssenKrupp's stainless steel division, Inoxum, including the stainless portion of the Calvert plant, was sold to Finnish stainless steel company Outokumpu in 2012.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The remaining portion of the ThyssenKrupp plant had final bids submitted by ArcelorMittal and Nippon Steel for $1.6 billion in March 2013.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Companhia Siderúrgica Nacional submitted a combined bid for the mill at Calvert, plus a majority stake in the ThyssenKrupp mill in Brazil, for $3.8 billion.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In July 2013, the plant was sold to ArcelorMittal and Nippon Steel.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The Hunt Refining Company, a subsidiary of Hunt Consolidated, Inc., is based in Tuscaloosa and operates a refinery there.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The company also operates terminals in Mobile, Melvin, and Moundville.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] JVC America, Inc. operates an optical disc replication and packaging plant in Tuscaloosa.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company operates a large plant in Gadsden which employs about 1,400 people.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Construction of an Airbus A320 family aircraft assembly plant in Mobile was formally announced by Airbus CEO Fabrice Brégier from the Mobile Convention Center on July 2, 2012.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The plans include a $600 million factory at the Brookley Aeroplex for the assembly of the A319, A320 and A321 aircraft.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Construction began in 2013, with plans for it to become operable by 2015 and produce up to 50 aircraft per year by 2017.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The assembly plant is the company's first factory to be built within the United States.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] It was announced on February 1, 2013, that Airbus had hired Alabama-based Hoar Construction to oversee construction of the facility.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The factory officially opened on September 14, 2015, covering one million square feet on 53 acres of flat grassland.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] According to Business Insider, Alabama ranked 14th in most popular states to visit in 2014.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] An estimated 26 million tourists visited the state in 2017 and spent $14.3 billion, providing directly or indirectly 186,900 jobs in the state, which includes 362,000 International tourists spending $589 million.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Mobile is known for having the oldest organized Mardi Gras celebration in the United States, beginning in 1703.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] It was also host to the first formally organized Mardi Gras parade in the U.S. in 1830, a tradition that continues to this day.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Mardi Gras is an official state holiday in Mobile and Baldwin counties.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In 2018, Mobile's Mardi Gras parade was the state's top event, producing the most tourists with an attendance of 892,811.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Space & Rocket Center in Huntsville with an attendance of 849,981, followed by the Birmingham Zoo with 543,090.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Of the parks and natural destinations, Alabama's Gulf Coast topped the list with 6,700,000 visitors.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama has historically been a popular region for film shoots due to its diverse landscapes and contrast of environments.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Movies filmed in Alabama include *Close Encounters of the Third Kind*, *Get Out*, *42*, *Selma*, *Big Fish*, *The Final Destination*, *Due Date*, and *Need for Speed*.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] UAB Hospital, USA Health University Hospital, Huntsville Hospital, and Children's Hospital of Alabama are the only Level I trauma centers in Alabama.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] UAB is the largest state government employer in Alabama, with a workforce of about 18,000.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] A 2017 study found that Alabama had the least competitive health insurance market in the country, with Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Alabama having a market share of 84% followed by UnitedHealth Group at 7%.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Regions Financial Corporation is the largest bank headquartered in or operating in Alabama.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] PNC Financial Services and Wells Fargo also have a major presence in Alabama.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Wells Fargo has a regional headquarters, an operations center campus, and a $400 million data center in Birmingham.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Many smaller banks are also headquartered in the Birmingham area, including ServisFirst and New South Federal Savings Bank.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Birmingham also serves as the headquarters for several large investment management companies, including Harbert Management Corporation.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Telecommunications provider AT&T, formerly BellSouth, has a major presence in Alabama with several large offices in Birmingham.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Many technology companies are headquartered in Huntsville, such as ADTRAN, a network access company; Intergraph, a computer graphics company; and Avocent, an IT infrastructure company.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Brasfield & Gorrie, BE&K, Hoar Construction, and B.L.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Harbert International, based in Alabama and subsidiaries of URS Corporation, are all routinely are included in the Engineering News-Record lists of top design, international construction, and engineering firms.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The foundational document for Alabama's government is the Alabama Constitution, the current constitution was adopted in 2022.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The former Alabama constitution adopted in 1901 was, with over 850 amendments and almost 87,000 words, by some accounts the world's longest constitution and roughly forty times the length of the United States Constitution.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] There was a significant movement to rewrite and modernize Alabama's constitution.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The former constitution was particularly criticized for its complexity and length intentionally codifying segregation and racism.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama's government is divided into three coequal branches.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The legislative branch is the Alabama Legislature, a bicameral assembly composed of the Alabama House of Representatives, with 105 members, and the Alabama Senate, with 35 members.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The Legislature is responsible for writing, debating, passing, or defeating state legislation.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The Republican Party currently holds a majority in both houses of the Legislature.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The Legislature has the power to override a gubernatorial veto by a simple majority (most state Legislatures require a two-thirds majority to override a veto).
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Until 1964, the state elected state senators on a geographic basis by county, with one per county.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] It had not redistricted congressional districts since passage of its constitution in 1901; as a result, urbanized areas were grossly underrepresented.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] It had not changed legislative districts to reflect the decennial censuses, either.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] At that time, Alabama and many other states had to change their legislative districting, as many across the country had systems that underrepresented urban areas and districts.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] This had caused decades of underinvestment in such areas.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] For instance, Birmingham and Jefferson County taxes had supplied one-third of the state budget, but Jefferson County received only 1/67th of state services in funding.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Through the legislative delegations, the Alabama legislature kept control of county governments.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The executive branch is responsible for the execution and oversight of laws.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] It is headed by the governor of Alabama.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Other members of the executive branch include the cabinet, the lieutenant governor of Alabama, the Attorney General of Alabama, the Alabama Secretary of State, the Alabama State Treasurer, and the State Auditor of Alabama.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The current governor is Republican Kay Ivey.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The members of the Legislature take office immediately after the November elections.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Statewide officials, such as the governor, lieutenant governor, attorney general, and other constitutional officers, take office the following January.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The judiciary is responsible for interpreting the Constitution of Alabama and applying the law in state criminal and civil cases.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The state's highest court is the Supreme Court of Alabama.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama uses partisan elections to select judges.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Since the 1980s judicial campaigns have become increasingly politicized.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The current chief justice of the Alabama Supreme Court is Republican Tom Parker.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] All sitting justices on the Alabama Supreme Court are members of the Republican Party.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] There are two intermediate appellate courts, the Court of Civil Appeals and the Court of Criminal Appeals, and four trial courts: the circuit court (trial court of general jurisdiction), and the district, probate, and municipal courts.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama has the death penalty with authorized methods of execution that include the electric chair and the gas chamber.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Some critics believe the election of judges has contributed to an exceedingly high rate of executions.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama has the highest per capita death penalty rate in the country.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In some years, it imposes more death sentences than does Texas, a state which has a population five times larger.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] However, executions per capita are significantly higher in Texas.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Some of its cases have been highly controversial; the U.S.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Supreme Court has overturned 83 convictions in death penalty cases.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] It was the only state to allow judges to override jury decisions in whether or not to use a death sentence; in 10 cases judges overturned sentences of life imprisonment without parole that were voted unanimously by juries.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] This judicial authority was removed in April 2017.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] On May 14, 2019, Alabama passed the Human Life Protection Act, banning abortion at any stage of pregnancy unless there is a "serious health risk", with no exceptions for rape and incest.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The law subjects doctors who perform abortions with 10 to 99 years imprisonment.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The law was originally supposed to take effect the following November, but on October 29, 2019, U.S.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] District Judge Myron Thompson blocked the law from taking effect due to it being in conflict with the 1973 U.S.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, Judge Thompson lifted the injunction, allowing the law to go into effect.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama is one of five to not operate a state lottery and one of just two states, the other being Utah, that prohibits the creation of state lotteries in their constitutions.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Taxes are collected by the Alabama Department of Revenue.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama levies a 2%, 4%, or 5% personal income tax, depending on the amount earned and filing status.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Taxpayers are allowed to deduct their federal income tax from their Alabama state tax, even if taking the standard deduction; those who itemize can also deduct FICA (the Social Security and Medicare tax).
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The state's general sales tax rate is 4%.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Sales tax rates for cities and counties are also added to purchases.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] For example, the total sales tax rate in Mobile County is 10% and there is an additional restaurant tax of 1%, which means a diner in Mobile County would pay an 11% tax on a meal.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In 2020, sales and excise taxes in Alabama accounted for 38% of all state and local revenue.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama gradually reduced the grocery tax to 2% between 2024 and 2025.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In April 2026, Alabama paused the grocery tax for the months of May and July of that year.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The corporate income tax rate in Alabama is 6.5%.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The overall federal, state, and local tax burden in Alabama ranks the state as the second least tax-burdened state in the country.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Property taxes of 0.40% of assessed value per year, are the second-lowest in the U.S., after Hawaii.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The state constitution currently requires a voter referendum to raise property taxes.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Historically, an Alabama excise tax "on the storage, use or other consumption in this state of tangible personal property purchased at retail for storage, use or other consumption in this state" was the focus of a 1941 U S Supreme Court ruling, *Curry v United States*.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Each county has its own elected legislative branch, usually called the county commission.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] It also has limited executive authority in the county.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Because of the constraints of the Alabama Constitution, which centralizes power in the state legislature, only seven counties (Jefferson, Lee, Mobile, Madison, Montgomery, Shelby, and Tuscaloosa) in the state have limited home rule.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Instead, most counties in the state must lobby the Local Legislation Committee of the state legislature to get simple local policies approved, ranging from waste disposal to land use zoning.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The state legislature has retained power over local governments by refusing to pass a constitutional amendment establishing home rule for counties, as recommended by the 1973 Alabama Constitutional Commission.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Legislative delegations retain certain powers over each county.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] United States Supreme Court decisions in *Baker v.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Carr* (1964) required that both houses have districts established on the basis of population, and redistricted after each census, to implement the principle of "one man, one vote".
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Before that, each county was represented by one state senator, leading to under-representation in the state senate for more urbanized, populous counties.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The rural bias of the state legislature, which had also failed to redistrict seats in the state house, affected politics well into the 20th century, failing to recognize the rise of industrial cities and urbanized areas.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] "The lack of home rule for counties in Alabama has resulted in the proliferation of local legislation permitting counties to do things not authorized by the state constitution.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama's constitution has been amended more than 700 times, and almost one-third of the amendments are local in nature, applying to only one county or city.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama is an alcoholic beverage control state, meaning the state government holds a monopoly on the sale of alcohol.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The Alabama Alcoholic Beverage Control Board controls the sale and distribution of alcoholic beverages in the state.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] A total of 25 of the 67 counties are "dry counties" which ban the sale of alcohol, and there are many dry municipalities in counties which permit alcohol sales.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] During Reconstruction following the American Civil War, Alabama was occupied by federal troops of the Third Military District under General John Pope.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In 1874, the political coalition of white Democrats known as the Redeemers took control of the state government from the Republicans, in part by suppressing the black vote through violence, fraud, and intimidation.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] After 1890, a coalition of White Democratic politicians passed laws to segregate and disenfranchise African American residents, a process completed in provisions of the 1901 constitution.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Provisions which disenfranchised blacks resulted in excluding many poor Whites.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] By 1941 more Whites than Blacks had been disenfranchised: 600,000 to 520,000.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The total effects were greater on the black community, as almost all its citizens were disfranchised and relegated to separate and unequal treatment under the law.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] From 1901 through the 1960s, the state did not redraw election districts as population grew and shifted within the state during urbanization and industrialization of certain areas.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] As counties were the basis of election districts, the result was a rural minority that dominated state politics through nearly three-quarters of the century, until a series of federal court cases required redistricting in 1972 to meet equal representation.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama state politics gained nationwide and international attention in the 1950s and 1960s during the civil rights movement, when whites bureaucratically, and at times violently, resisted protests for electoral and social reform.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Governor George Wallace, the state's only four-term governor, was a controversial figure who vowed to maintain segregation.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Only after passage of the federal Civil Rights Act of 1964 and Voting Rights Act of 1965 did African Americans regain the ability to exercise suffrage, among other civil rights.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In many jurisdictions, they continued to be excluded from representation by at-large electoral systems, which allowed the majority of the population to dominate elections.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Some changes at the county level have occurred following court challenges to establish single-member districts that enable a more diverse representation among county boards.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In 2007, the Alabama Legislature passed, and Republican governor Bob Riley signed a resolution expressing "profound regret" over slavery and its lingering impact.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In a symbolic ceremony, the bill was signed in the Alabama State Capitol, which housed Congress of the Confederate States of America.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In 2010, Republicans won control of both houses of the legislature for the first time in 136 years.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] As of February 2023, there are a total of 3,707,233 registered voters, with 3,318,679 active, and the others inactive in the state.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The 2023 *American Values Atlas* by Public Religion Research Institute found that a majority of Alabama residents support same-sex marriage.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] With the disfranchisement of Blacks in 1901, the state became part of the "Solid South", a system in which the Democratic Party operated as effectively the only viable political party in every Southern state.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] For nearly a hundred years local and state elections in Alabama were decided in the Democratic Party primary, with generally only token Republican challengers running in the general election.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Since the mid- to late 20th century, however, white conservatives started shifting to the Republican Party.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In Alabama, majority-white districts are now expected to regularly elect Republican candidates to federal, state and local office.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Members of the nine seats on the Supreme Court of Alabama and all ten seats on the state appellate courts are elected to office.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Until 1994, no Republicans held any of the court seats.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In that general election, the then-incumbent chief justice, Ernest C.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Hornsby, refused to leave office after losing the election by approximately 3,000 votes to Republican Perry O.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Hornsby sued Alabama and defiantly remained in office for nearly a year before finally giving up the seat after losing in court.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The Democrats lost the last of the nineteen court seats in August 2011 with the resignation of the last Democrat on the bench.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In the early 21st century, Republicans hold all seven of the statewide elected executive branch offices.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Republicans hold six of the eight elected seats on the Alabama State Board of Education.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In 2010, Republicans took large majorities of both chambers of the state legislature, giving them control of that body for the first time in 136 years.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The last remaining statewide Democrat, who served on the Alabama Public Service Commission, was defeated in 2012.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Only three Republican lieutenant governors have been elected since the end of Reconstruction, when Republicans generally represented Reconstruction government, including the newly emancipated freedmen who had gained the franchise.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The three GOP lieutenant governors are Steve Windom (1999–2003), Kay Ivey (2011–2017), and Will Ainsworth (2019–present).
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Many metropolitan and suburban counties have voters who are majority Democrats, resulting in local elections being decided in the Democratic primary.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Similarly, most rural counties are majority-Republican and elections are effectively decided in the Republican primary.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] However, since local governments in Alabama are weaker than in other parts of the country, Republicans have the upper hand in government.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama's 67 county sheriffs are elected in partisan, at-large races, and Republicans retain the vast majority of those posts.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The current split is 18 Democrats, and 49 Republicans as of 2023.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] However, most of the Democratic sheriffs preside over urban and more populated counties.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The majority of Republican sheriffs have been elected in the more rural counties with lower population.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] As of 2025, the state of Alabama has 11 African-American sheriffs.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The state's two U.S. senators are Katie Britt and Tommy Tuberville, both of whom are Republican.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] House of Representatives, the state is represented by seven members, five of whom are Republicans (Mike Rogers, Robert Aderholt, Dale Strong, Barry Moore, and Gary Palmer) and two Democrats (Terri Sewell and Shomari Figures).
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Public primary and secondary education in Alabama is under the purview of the Alabama State Board of Education as well as local oversight by 67 county school boards and 60 city boards of education.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Together, 1,496 individual schools provide education for 744,637 elementary and secondary students.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Public school funding is appropriated through the Alabama Legislature through the Education Trust Fund.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] That represented an increase of $444,736,387 over the previous fiscal year.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In 2007, more than 82 percent of schools made Adequate Yearly Progress (AYP) toward student proficiency under the National No Child Left Behind law, using measures determined by the state of Alabama.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] While Alabama's public education system has improved in recent decades, it lags behind in achievement compared to other states.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Census data (2000), Alabama's high school graduation rate (75%) is the fourth lowest in the U.S.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] (after Kentucky, Louisiana and Mississippi).
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The largest educational gains were among people with some college education but without degrees.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] According to National Assessment of Educational Progress (NEAP), Alabama ranks 39 in reading and 40 in math among fourth-grade students in the rankings from 2022.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Generally prohibited in the West at large, school corporal punishment is not unusual in Alabama, with 27,260 public school students paddled at least one time, according to government data for the 2011–2012 school year.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The rate of school corporal punishment in Alabama is surpassed by only Mississippi and Arkansas.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama's programs of higher education include 14 four-year public universities, two-year community colleges, and 17 private, undergraduate and graduate universities.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Public, post-secondary education in Alabama is overseen by the Alabama Commission on Higher Education and the Alabama Department of Postsecondary Education.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Colleges and universities in Alabama offer degree programs from two-year associate degrees to a multitude of doctoral level programs.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The largest single campus in Alabama is Tuskegee University with 5000 acres.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The largest student body is the University of Alabama, located in Tuscaloosa, with 42,360 students enrolled for fall 2025.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Troy University was the largest institution in the state in 2010, with an enrollment of 29,689 students across four Alabama campuses (Troy, Dothan, Montgomery, and Phenix City), as well as sixty learning sites in seventeen other states and eleven other countries.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The oldest institutions are the public University of North Alabama in Florence and the Catholic Church-affiliated Spring Hill College in Mobile, both founded in 1830.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] News & World Report*, Alabama had three universities ranked in the top 100 Public Schools in America (Auburn University at 47, University of Alabama at Birmingham (UAB) at 76, and University of Alabama at 91).
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] News & World Report*, Alabama had four tier one universities (Auburn University, University of Alabama at Birmingham (UAB), University of Alabama and University of Alabama in Huntsville).
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Major newspapers include *Birmingham News*, Mobile *Press-Register*, and *Montgomery Advertiser*.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama literature is characterized by themes of race and issues of gender and war, and is influenced by events such as the American Civil War, the Reconstruction era, the civil rights movement, and the Vietnam War.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Some notable examples of Alabama literature include Harper Lee's *To Kill a Mockingbird*, Winston Groom's *Forrest Gump*, Fannie Flagg's *Fried Green Tomatoes at the Whistle Stop Cafe*, and the biographies of Rosa Parks and Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama has several professional and semi-professional sports teams, including three minor league baseball teams.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The Talladega Superspeedway motorsports complex hosts a series of NASCAR events.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] It has a seating capacity of 143,000 and is the thirteenth largest stadium in the world and sixth largest stadium in America.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Also, the Barber Motorsports Park has hosted IndyCar Series and Rolex Sports Car Series races.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The ATP Birmingham was a World Championship Tennis tournament held from 1973 to 1980.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama has hosted several professional golf tournaments, such as the 1984 and 1990 PGA Championship at Shoal Creek, the Barbasol Championship (PGA Tour), the Mobile LPGA Tournament of Champions, Airbus LPGA Classic, and Yokohama Tire LPGA Classic (LPGA Tour), and The Tradition (Champions Tour).
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] College football is extremely popular in Alabama, particularly the University of Alabama Crimson Tide and Auburn University Tigers, rivals in the Southeastern Conference.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Alabama averages over 100,000 fans per game and Auburn averages over 80,000—both numbers among the top twenty in the nation.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Bryant–Denny Stadium is the home of the Alabama football team, and has a seating capacity of 101,821, and is the fifth largest stadium in America.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Jordan-Hare Stadium is the home field of the Auburn football team and seats up to 87,451.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Protective Stadium is home of the UAB Blazers football program and the Birmingham Bowl.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Opening in 2020, Hancock Whitney Stadium in Mobile is the home of the University of South Alabama football team, and serves as the home of the Reese's Senior Bowl, the AHSAA North/South All-star Game, and the LendingTree Bowl; the stadium seats 25,450.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In 2009, Bryant–Denny Stadium and Jordan-Hare Stadium became the homes of the Alabama High School Athletic Association state football championship games, after previously being held at Legion Field in Birmingham.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] For rail transport, Amtrak schedules the *Crescent*, a daily passenger train, running from New York to New Orleans with station stops at Anniston, Birmingham, and Tuscaloosa.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The *Mardi Gras Service* operates daily between Mobile and New Orleans; the Mobile terminus is its only Alabama stop.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] I-22 enters the state from Mississippi and connects Birmingham with Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] In addition, there are currently five auxiliary interstate routes in the state: I-165 in Mobile, I-359 in Tuscaloosa, I-459 around Birmingham, I-565 in Decatur and Huntsville, and I-759 in Gadsden.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] A sixth route, I-685, will be formed when I-85 is rerouted along a new southern bypass of Montgomery.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] A proposed northern bypass of Birmingham will be designated as I-422.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Since a direct connection from I-22 to I-422 will not be possible, I-222 has been proposed, as well.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] Highways also pass through the state, such as U.S.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] There are four toll roads in the state: Montgomery Expressway in Montgomery; Northport/Tuscaloosa Western Bypass in Tuscaloosa and Northport; Emerald Mountain Expressway in Wetumpka; and Beach Express in Orange Beach.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The Port of Mobile, Alabama's only saltwater port, is a large seaport on the Gulf of Mexico with inland waterway access to the Midwest by way of the Tennessee–Tombigbee Waterway.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The Port of Mobile was ranked 12th by tons of traffic in the United States during 2009.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The newly expanded container terminal at the Port of Mobile was ranked as the 25th busiest for container traffic in the nation during 2011.
[src:adx-florence/alabama-p02] The state's other ports are on rivers with access to the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The United States Department of Justice acquired the United States Disciplinary Barracks, Pacific Branch, on Alcatraz on October 12, 1933.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The island became adapted and used as a prison of the Federal Bureau of Prisons in August 1934 after the buildings were modernized and security increased.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Given this high security and the island's location in the cold waters and strong currents of San Francisco Bay, prison operators believed Alcatraz to be escape-proof and America's most secure prison.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The three-story cellhouse included the four main cell blocks – A-block to D-block – the warden's office, visitation room, the library, and the barber shop.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The prison cells typically measured 9 feet (2.7 m) by 5 ft (1.5 m) and 7 ft (2.1 m) high.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The cells were primitive and lacked privacy.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] They were furnished with a bed, desk, washbasin, a toilet on the back wall, and few items other than a blanket.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] D-Block housed the worst inmates, and six cells at its end were designated "The Hole".
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Prisoners with behavioral problems were sent to these for periods of often brutal punishment.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The dining hall and kitchen extended from the main building.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Prisoners and staff ate three meals a day together.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The Alcatraz Hospital was located above the dining hall.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Prison corridors were named after major U.S. streets, such as Broadway and Michigan Avenue, of New York City and Chicago, respectively.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Working at the prison was considered a privilege for inmates.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Those who earned privileges were employed in the Model Industries Building and New Industries Building during the day, actively involved in providing for the military in jobs such as sewing and woodwork, and performing maintenance and laundry chores.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] From 1969 to 1971, the island and prison were occupied by Native Americans.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] It is one of San Francisco's major tourist attractions, attracting some 1.5 million visitors annually.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Now operated by the National Park Service's Golden Gate National Recreation Area, the former prison is being restored and maintained.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The main cellhouse was built incorporating some parts of Fort Alcatraz's citadel, a partially fortified barracks from 1859 that was used as a jail during the Civil War for alleged Confederate sympathizers.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Weller, the Chairman of the State Democratic Committee and brother of California Governor John B.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Weller, was one of the first prisoners housed there.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Upon completion, the 500-foot (150 m) long concrete building was reputedly the longest concrete building in the world at the time.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] This building was modernized in 1933 and 1934 and became the main cellhouse of the federal penitentiary.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] When the new concrete prison was built, many materials were reused in its construction.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Iron staircases in the interior and the cellhouse door near the barber's shop at the end of A-block were retained from the old citadel.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Massive granite blocks originally used as gun mounts were reused as the wharf's bulkheads and retaining walls.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Many of the old cell bars were used to reinforce the walls; many placed near the edge were subject to erosion from the salt air and wind over the years.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] After the United States Army's use of the island for over 80 years, it was transferred to the Federal Bureau of Prisons, which hoped an escape-proof jail would help break the crime wave of the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The Department of Justice acquired the Disciplinary Barracks on Alcatraz on October 12, 1933, and it became a Federal Bureau of Prisons facility in August 1934. $260,000 was spent to modernize and improve it from January 1934.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] George Hess of the United States Public Health Service was appointed the chief medical officer.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Twitchell became a consultant in psychiatry for Alcatraz in January 1934.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The on site hospital was checked by three officials from the Marine Hospital of San Francisco.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The Bureau of Prisons personnel arrived on Alcatraz in early February 1934; among them was acting chief clerk Loring O.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] In April, the old material was removed from the prison.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Holes were cut in the concrete and 269 cell fronts were installed, built using four carloads of steel ordered from the Stewart Iron Works.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Two of four new stairways were built, as were 12 doors to the utility corridors and gratings at the top of the cells.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] On 26 April, a small accidental fire broke out on the roof and an electrician injured his foot by dropping a manhole cover on it.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The Anchor Post Fence Company added fencing around Alcatraz and the Enterprise Electric Works added emergency lighting in the morgue and switchboard operations.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] In June 1934, the Teletouch Corporation of New York began the installation of an "electro-magnetic gun or metal detecting system" at Alcatraz; detectors were added on the wharf, at the front entrance into the cellblock, and at the rear entrance gate.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The correctional officers were instructed on how to operate the new locking devices in July 1934, and both the United States Coast Guard and the San Francisco Police Department tested the new radio equipment.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Final checks and assessments were made on the first two days of August.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Alcatraz was intended for prisoners who continuously caused trouble at other federal prisons.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] It would be a "last resort prison", to hold the worst of the worst who had no hope of rehabilitation.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] On August 11, 1934, the first group of 137 prisoners arrived at Alcatraz from the United States Penitentiary in Leavenworth, Kansas, having traveled by rail to Santa Venetia, California.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Before being escorted to Alcatraz, they were handcuffed in high-security coaches and guarded by some 60 Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) special agents, U.S.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Marshals, and railway security officials.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Most of the prisoners were notorious bank robbers, counterfeiters, or murderers.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Among the first inmates were also 14 men from McNeil Island, Washington.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] On August 22, 1934, 43 prisoners arrived from Atlanta Penitentiary and 10 from North Eastern Penitentiary, Lewisburg, Pennsylvania.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] On 1 September, one prisoner arrived from Washington Asylum and Jail and seven from the District of Columbia Reformatory in Virginia, and on 4 September, another batch of 103 prisoners arrived by train from Leavenworth.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Prisoners continued to arrive, mainly from Leavenworth and Atlanta, into 1935 and by June 30, 1935, the penitentiary's first anniversary, it had a population of 242 prisoners, although some inmates such as Verrill Rapp had already been transferred from Alcatraz some months earlier.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] On Alcatraz's first anniversary, the Bureau of Prisons wrote, "The establishment of this institution not only provided a secure place for the detention of the more difficult type of criminal, but has had a good effect upon discipline in our other penitentiaries also.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] No serious disturbance of any kind has been reported during the year." The metal detectors often overheated and had to be turned off.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] After the Teletouch Corporation failed to address the problem, their contract was terminated in 1937 and they were charged over $200 (equivalent to about $4479 in 2025) for three new detectors supplied by Federal Laboratories.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] On January 10, 1935, a severe storm caused a landslide on Alcatraz, causing the Model Industries Building to slide.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] This prompted a series of changes to the structures on the island.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] A riprap was built around the Model Industries Building, it was strengthened, and a guard tower added to the roof in June 1936.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] That same month, the barracks building was remodeled into 11 new apartments and nine single rooms for bachelors; by this time there were 52 families living on Alcatraz, including 126 women and children.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The changes were completed in July 1941.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The workshops of the New Industries Building became highly productive, making Army uniforms, cargo nets, and other items in high demand during World War II.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] In June 1945, it was reported that the federal penitentiaries had made 60,000 nets.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Alcatraz gained notoriety from its inception as the toughest prison in the U.S., considered by many the world's most fearsome prison of the day.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Former prisoners reported brutality and inhumane conditions which severely tested their sanity.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Ed Wutke was the first prisoner to commit suicide in Alcatraz.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Rufe Persful chopped off his fingers after grabbing an axe from the firetruck, begging another inmate to do the same to his other hand.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] One writer described Alcatraz as "the great garbage can of San Francisco Bay, into which every federal prison dumped its most rotten apples".
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The prison's reputation was not helped by the arrival of more of America's most dangerous felons, including Robert Stroud, the "Birdman of Alcatraz", in 1942.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] He entered the prison system at the age of 19, and never left, spending 17 years at Alcatraz.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Stroud killed a guard, tangled with other inmates and spent 42 of his 54 years in prison in solitary confinement.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Despite its reputation, with many former inmates calling it "Hellcatraz", some prisoners reported that the living conditions there were much better than most other prisons in the country, especially the food, and many volunteered to come to Alcatraz.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] On December 3, 1940, Henri Young murdered fellow inmate Rufus McCain.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Running downstairs from the furniture shop to the tailor's shop where McCain worked, Young violently stabbed McCain in the neck; McCain died five hours later.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Young had been sent to Alcatraz for murder in 1933, and was later involved in an escape attempt during which gangster Doc Barker was shot to death.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] He spent nearly 22 months in solitary confinement as a result, but was eventually permitted to work in the furniture shop.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Young went to trial in 1941, with his attorneys claiming that their client could not be held responsible for the murder, since he had allegedly been subjected to "cruel and unusual punishment" by prison guards prior to the act.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The trial brought Alcatraz into further disrepute.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Ultimately, Young was convicted of manslaughter and his prison sentence was extended by a few years.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] By the 1950s, conditions at Alcatraz had improved, and inmates were gradually permitted more privileges, such as playing musical instruments, watching movies on weekends, painting, and radio use; the strict code of silence became more relaxed, and prisoners were permitted to talk quietly.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] However, it was by far the most expensive prison in the United States, and many still perceived it as America's most extreme jail.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] In his annual report for 1952, Bureau of Prisons Director James V.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Bennett called for a more centralized institution to replace Alcatraz.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] A 1959 report indicated that the facility was over three times more expensive to run than the average American prison; $10 per prisoner per day compared to $3 in most other prisons.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The problem was made worse by the buildings' structural deterioration from exposure to salt spray, which would require $5 million to fix.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Major repairs began in 1958, but by 1961 engineers considered the prison a lost cause.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Kennedy submitted plans for a new maximum-security institution at Marion, Illinois.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The June 1962 escape from Alcatraz led to acrimonious investigations.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Combined with the major structural problems and expensive operation, this led to its closure on March 21, 1963.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The former prison and island are now a museum.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] It is one of San Francisco's major tourist attractions drawing in some 1.5 million visitors annually (2010).
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Visitors arrive by boat and are given a tour of the cellhouse and island, and a slide show and audio narration with anecdotes from former inmates, guards and rangers on Alcatraz.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The atmosphere of the former penitentiary is still considered to be "eerie", "ghostly" and "chilling".
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Protected by the National Park Service and the National Register of Historic Places, the salt-damaged buildings of the former prison are now being restored and maintained.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] On May 4, 2025, President Donald Trump proposed reopening the prison for "America's most ruthless and violent offenders".
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Historians and prison experts said that, while the reopening of the prison would be symbolic for Trump, it would be costly to renovate and maintain; Trump himself said that, if Alcatraz were reopened, the prison would need to be renovated extensively.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] According to the prison's correctional officers, once a convict arrived on the Alcatraz wharf, his first thoughts were on how to leave.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] During its 29 years of operation, the penitentiary claimed that no prisoner successfully escaped.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] A total of 36 prisoners made 14 escape attempts, two men trying twice.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Twenty-three were caught, six were shot and killed during their escape, two drowned, and five are listed as "missing and presumed drowned".
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The first escape attempt was made on April 27, 1936, by Joseph Bowers, who was assigned to burn trash at the incinerator.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] He was scaling a chain link fence at the edge of the island when noticed.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] When he refused orders of the correctional officer located at the West Road guard tower to come down, he was shot.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] He was seriously injured in the fall from over 15 m (50 ft) and consequently died.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The second escape attempt was on December 16, 1937, by Theodore Cole and Ralph Roe.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] During their work assignment in one of the workshops, they cut the flat iron bars of the window and climbed into the bay.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] It was a stormy day and the sea was rough.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Though never found, prison authorities presumed them to have died, assuming they drowned in the bay and their bodies were swept out to sea.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The most violent escape attempt occurred on May 2–4, 1946, when a failed attempt by six prisoners led to the Battle of Alcatraz, also known as the "Alcatraz Blast Out".
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Bernard Coy, Joseph Cretzer, Sam Shockley, Clarence Carnes, Marvin Hubbard and Miran Thompson took control of the cell house by overpowering correctional officers, and were able to enter the weapons room, where they then demanded keys to the outside recreation door.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] A quick-thinking guard, William Miller, turned over all but the key to the outer door, which he pocketed.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The prisoners' aim was to escape by boat from the dock, but when they were unable to open the outside door, they decided to battle it out.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] They held Miller and a second guard hostage.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Prompted by Shockley and Thompson, Cretzer shot the hostages at very close range.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Miller succumbed to his injuries while the second guard, Harold Stites, was also killed at the cell house.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Although Shockley, Thompson, and Carnes returned to their cells, the other three, Coy, Cretzer and Hubbard, persisted with their fight.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Marines intervened and killed the three prisoners.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] In this battle, apart from the guards and prisoners killed, 17 other guards and one prisoner were also injured.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Shockley, Thompson, and Carnes were tried for the killing of the correctional officers.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Shockley and Thompson were sentenced to death in the gas chamber, which was carried out at San Quentin in December 1948.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] However, Carnes, who was only 19 years of age, was given a second life sentence.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] On June 11, 1962, Frank Morris, John Anglin, and Clarence Anglin attempted to escape using careful planning.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Behind their cells in Cell Block B was a 3-foot (0.91 m) wide unguarded utility corridor.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The prisoners chiseled away the salt-damaged concrete from around an air vent leading to this corridor, using tools such as a metal spoon soldered with silver from a dime and an electric drill improvised from a stolen vacuum cleaner motor.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The noise was disguised by accordions played during music hour, and the progress was concealed by false walls which, in the dark recesses of the cells, fooled the guards.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The escape route led up through a fan vent.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The prisoners removed the fan and motor, replacing them with a steel grille and leaving a shaft large enough for a prisoner to enter.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Stealing a carborundum abrasive cord from the prison workshop, the prisoners then removed the rivets from the grille.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] In their beds, they placed papier-mâché dummies made with human hair stolen from the barbershop.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Over many weeks, the escapees made an inflatable raft from over 50 stolen raincoats, which they prepared on the top of the cell block, concealed from the guards by sheets which had been put up over the sides.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] They escaped through a vent in the roof and departed Alcatraz.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The FBI investigation was aided by another prisoner, Allen West, who was part of the escapees' group, but was left behind.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] West's false wall kept slipping so he held it in place with cement, which set.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] When Morris and the Anglins accelerated the schedule, West desperately chipped away at the wall, but by the time he got out, his companions were gone.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Hundreds of leads and theories have been pursued by the FBI and local law enforcement officials in the ensuing years, but no conclusive evidence has ever surfaced favoring the success or failure of the attempt.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The FBI's investigation was eventually closed in December 1979.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The United States Marshals Service case file remains open and active.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Morris and the Anglin brothers remain on its wanted list.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The prison initially had a staff of 155, including the first warden James A.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Shuttleworth, both considered to be "iron men".
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] None of the staff were trained in rehabilitation, but were highly trained in security.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The guards' and staff's salaries varied.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] A new guard arriving in December 1948 was offered $3,024.96 per year, but there was a 6% deduction for retirement taxes a year (amounting to $181.50).
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The guards typically worked 40-hour weeks with five 8-hour shifts.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Guards who worked between 6 pm and 6 am were given a 10% increase and guards doing overtime had to be reported and authorized by the warden.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Officers generally had to pay 25 cents for meals and were charged $10 to rent an apartment on the island, to include laundry service, although larger families were charged anything from $20–43 a month for larger quarters and charged additional for laundry.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] In 1960, a Bureau of Prisons booklet revealed that the average prison population between 1935 and 1960 was 263; the highest recorded was 302 in 1937 and the lowest recorded was 222 in 1947.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The main administration center was at the entrance to the prison, which included the warden's office.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The office contained a desk with radio and telegraph equipment, typewriter, and a telephone.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The basement of Alcatraz prison contained dungeons and the showers.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The main stairway to the dungeon lay along Sunrise Alley at the side of A-Block, but the dungeons were also accessible by a staircase in a trapdoor along the corridor of D-Block.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] All visits to Alcatraz required prior written approval from the warden.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] A hospital had originally been installed at Alcatraz during its time as a military prison in the late 19th century.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] During its time as a federal penitentiary, it was located above the dining hall on the second floor.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Public Health Service employees assigned to the Federal Prison Service at Alcatraz.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Doctors often lasted fewer than several days or months at Alcatraz, because few of them could tolerate the violent inmates who would often terrify them if they failed to be given certain drugs.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Prisoners in ill health were often kept in the hospital, most famously Stroud and Al Capone, who spent years in it.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] When the Bureau of Prisons established the Federal Penitentiary on January 1, 1934, they took measures to strengthen the security of the prison cells to make Alcatraz "escape-proof" and improve living conditions for their own staff.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Up-to-date technologies for enhancing security and comfort were added to the buildings.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Guard towers were built outside at four strategic locations, cells were rebuilt and fitted with "tool-proof steel cell fronts and locking devices operated from control boxes," and windows were made covered with iron grilles.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Electromagnetic metal detectors were placed at the entrances of the dining hall and workshops, with remote controlled tear gas canisters at appropriate locations and gun galleries with machine gun armed guards were installed to patrol along the corridors.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Attorney General Homer Cummings, and Sanford Bates, first director of the Bureau of Prisons, collaborated very closely to create "a legendary prison" suited to the times, which resulted in the Alcatraz Island Federal Penitentiary being nicknamed "Uncle Sam's Devil's Island".
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Prisoners entering Alcatraz would undergo vigorous research and assessments prior to their arrival.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Security in the prison was very tight, with constant checking of bars, doors, locks, electrical fixtures, and other physical security.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Prisoners were normally counted 13 times daily, and the ratio of prisoners to guards was the lowest of any American prison of the time.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The front door was made of solid steel, virtually impossible for any prisoners to escape through.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The island had many guard towers, most of which have since been demolished, which were heavily guarded at various points in the day at times when security may have been breached.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] For instance, there were guard towers on each of the industry buildings to ensure that inmates didn't attempt to escape during the work day shifts.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The recreation yard and other parts of the prison had a 25-foot fence around it topped with barbed wire, should any inmates attempt to escape during exercise.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] One former employee of the jail likened his prison job to being a zoo keeper or his old farm job, due to the fact that prisoners were treated like animals, sending them out to "plow the fields" when some of them worked during the day, and then counting them up and feeding them and so on.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] He referred to those four years of his life working in the prison as a "total waste of his life".
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The corridors were regularly patrolled by the guards, with passing gates along them.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The most heavily trafficked corridor was "Broadway" between B and C Block, due to its being the central corridor of the prison and passed by guards and other prison workers.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] At the end of each 20-minute meal in the dining hall, the forks, spoons and knives were laid out on the table and carefully counted to ensure that nothing had been taken as a potential weapon.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] In the earlier years as a prison, prisoners were forbidden from talking while eating, but this was later relaxed, provided that the prisoners communicated quietly.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The gun gallery was situated in the Recreation Yard and mounted on one of the dining hall's exterior walls.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] There was a metal detector outside of the dining hall for security purposes.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The dining hall had tear gas canisters attached to the rafters of the ceiling, which could be activated by remote control, should prisoners riot or attempt to escape.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Johnston, always entered the dining hall alone and unarmed, due to heavy guarding around him.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Several riots broke out in the dining hall during Alcatraz's history.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Those prisoners who were not involved in the fighting hid under the dining hall tables to escape possible gunfire.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] An inmate register reveals that there were 1,576 prisoners in total held at Alcatraz during its time as a Federal Penitentiary, although figures reported have varied and some have stated 1,557.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The prison cells, purposefully designed so that none adjoined an outside wall, typically measured 9 feet (2.7 m) by 5 ft (1.5 m) and 7 ft (2.1 m) high.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The cells were primitive with a bed, a desk and a washbasin and toilet on the back wall and few furnishings, except a blanket.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] An air vent, measuring 6 inches (150 mm) by 9 in (230 mm), covered by a metal grille, lay at the back of the cells, which led into the utility corridors.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Prisoners had no privacy in going to the toilet and the toilets would emit a strong stench, because they were flushed with salt water.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Hot water taps were not installed until the early 1960s, shortly before closure.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Copies of these were provided to the prisoners to read and follow.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Inmates were basically entitled to food, clothing, shelter, and medical attention.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Inmates were given a blue shirt, grey pants (blue and white in later years), webbed belt, cotton long underwear, socks and a blue handkerchief; the wearing of caps was forbidden in the cellhouse.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Cells were expected to be kept tidy and in good order.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Any dangerous article found in the cells or on inmates such as money, narcotics, intoxicating substances or tools which had the potential to inflict injury or assist in an escape attempt was considered contraband and made the prisoners eligible for disciplinary action.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] It was compulsory for prisoners to shave in their cells three times a week.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Attempting to bribe, intimidate, or assault prison officers was seen as a very serious offense.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] African-Americans were segregated from the rest in cell designation due to racial abuse being prevalent.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Toilet paper, matches, soap, and cleanser were issued to the cells on Tuesdays and Saturdays, and inmates could request hot water and a mop to clean their cells.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The bars, windows and floors of the prison were cleaned on a daily basis.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] In earlier years there was a strict code of silence, but by the 1950s this had relaxed and talking was permitted in the cellhouse and dining hall, provided conversations were quiet and there was no shouting, loud talking, whistling or singing.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Prisoners would be awakened at 6:30 a.m., and sent to breakfast at 6:55 a.m.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] After returning to the cell, inmates then had to tidy their cell and place the wastebasket outside.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] At 7:30 a.m., work started in the shifts for those privileged enough to do so, punctuated by a whistle, and prisoners would have to go through a metal detector during work shifts.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] If assigned a job, prisoners had to accept that line of work; prisoners were not permitted to have money in their possessions, but earnings went into a prisoner's Trust Fund.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Some of the prisoners were assigned duties with the guards and foremen in the Laundry, Tailor Shop, Cobblers Shop, Model Shop etc. and in gardening and labor.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Smoking, a privilege, was permitted in the workplace providing that it would not be hazardous, but inmates were not permitted to smoke between the recreation yard and work.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Lunch was served at 11:20 a.m., followed by a 30-minute rest in the cell, before returning to work until 4:15 p.m.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Dinner was served at 4:25 p.m. and the prisoners would then retire to their cells to be locked in for the night at 4:50 p.m.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] After being locked in for the night, six guards usually patrolled the four cell blocks.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Many prisoners have compared their duration at Alcatraz to hell and would have preferred death to continued incarceration.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Alcatraz Library was located at the end of D-Block.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Upon entering Alcatraz, every inmate was given a library card and a catalog of books found in the library.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Inmates could place orders by putting a slip with their card in a box at the entrance to the dining hall before breakfast, and the books would be delivered to and from their cell by a librarian.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The library, which utilized a closed-stack paging system, had a collection of 10,000 to 15,000 books, mainly left over from the army days.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Inmates were permitted a maximum of three books in addition to up to twelve text books, a Bible, and a dictionary.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] They were permitted to subscribe to magazines, but crime-related pages were torn out and newspapers were prohibited.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Sex, crime and violence were censored from all books and magazines, and the library was governed by a chaplain who regulated the censorship and the nature of the reading material to ensure that the material was wholesome.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Failure to return books by the date given made the inmate liable to removal of privileges.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The average prisoner read 75 to 100 books a year.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Every evening, inmates would generally read books loaned from the library and usually an hour or 75 minutes was allocated to the practicing of musical instruments, from the guitar to the accordion.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] A prison band often practiced in the dining room or auditorium above it.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Al Capone famously practiced the banjo in the shower block, although most prisoners were limited to playing in their cells alone.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Alcatraz cellhouse had a corridor naming system named after major American streets and landmarks.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Michigan Avenue was the corridor to the side of A-Block.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Broadway was the central corridor in which the inmates would assemble as they massed through Times Square (an area with a clock on the wall), before entering the dining hall for their meals.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Broadway separated Block-B and Block-C and prisoners kept along it had the least privacy in the prison.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The corridor between Block-C and the library was called Park Avenue.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The corridor in D-Block was named Sunset Strip.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Gun galleries lay at the end of each block, including the West and East Gun Galleries.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] A-Block was never modernized, so retained its "flat strap-iron bars, key locks and spiral staircases" from the original military prison.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] No inmates were permanently held there during the years Alcatraz was a federal penitentiary.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Several inmates, however, were held briefly in A-Block before a hearing or transfer.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] In the later years, A-Block was mainly used for storage.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] A law library was set up at some point, where inmates could type legal documents.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] A small barber's shop was located at the end of A-Block where inmates would have a monthly haircut.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Most new inmates at Alcatraz were assigned to the second tier of B-Block.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] They had "quarantine status" for their first three months in confinement in Alcatraz, and were not permitted visitors for a minimum of 90 days.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Inmates were permitted one visitor a month—although persons likely to cause trouble, such as registered criminals, were barred from visiting.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Letters received by inmates were checked by prison staff first, to see if they could decipher any secret messages.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Frank Morris and his fellow escapees escaped Alcatraz during the June 1962 Alcatraz escape attempt by entering a utility corridor behind B-Block.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] D-Block gained notoriety as a "treatment block" for some of the worst inmates, with varying degrees of punishment, including isolation, solitary confinement and strip searches.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Prisoners usually spent anywhere from 3 to 19 days in solitary confinement.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Prisoners held here would be given their meals in their cells, were not permitted to work and could only shower twice a week.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] After a 1939 escape attempt in which Arthur "Doc" Barker was killed, the Bureau of Prisons tightened security in the D-Block.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The Birdman of Alcatraz inhabited cell 42 in D-Block in solitary confinement for six years.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The worst cells for confinement as a punishment for inmates who stepped out of line were located at the end of D-Block in cells 9–14, known as "The Hole".
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Inmates held there were limited to just one 10-minute shower and an hour of exercise in the yard a week.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The five cells of "The Hole" had nothing but a sink and toilet; the very worst cell was the final cell, nicknamed "The Oriental" or "Strip Cell", which contained nothing but a hole in the floor as a toilet, and in which prisoners would often be confined naked with nothing else for two days.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The guards controlled the flushing of the toilet in the final cell.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] After completing the punishment in the Hole, the prisoner could then return to their cell, but would be tagged.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] A red tag, third grade, denoted a prisoner who was restricted from leaving their cell for perhaps three months.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] At second grade the prisoners could receive letters, and if after 30 days they remained well-behaved, they would then be restored full prison privileges.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] — Henri Young testifying his experiences in "The Hole" at Alcatraz during his 1941 trial.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Alcatraz Dining Hall, often referred to as the Mess Hall, is the dining hall where the prisoners and staff ate their meals.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] It is a long wing on the west end of the Main Cellhouse of Alcatraz, situated in the center of the island.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] It is connected to the block by a corridor known as "Times Square", as it passes beneath a large clock approaching the entrance way to the dining hall.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] This wing includes the dining hall and the kitchen beyond it.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] On the second floor were the hospital and the auditorium, which was where movies were screened to the inmates on weekends.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Dining hall protocol was a scripted process, including a whistle system to indicate which block and tier of men would move into and out of the hall at any given time, who sat where, where to place hands, and when to start eating.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Prisoners would be awakened at 6:30 am, and sent to breakfast at 6:55 am.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] A breakfast menu is still preserved on the hallway board, dated March 21, 1963.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The breakfast menu included assorted dry cereals, steamed whole wheat, a scrambled egg, milk, stewed fruit, toast, bread, and butter.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Lunch was served in the dining hall at 11:20 am, followed by a 30-minute rest in the cell, before returning to work until 16:15.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Dinner was served at 16:25 and the prisoners would then go to their cells at 16:50 to be locked in for the night.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Inmates were permitted to eat as much as they liked within 20 minutes, provided they left no waste.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Waste would be reported and made the prisoner subject to removal of privileges if they made a habit of it.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Each dining table had benches which held up to six men, although smaller tables and chairs later replaced these which seated four.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] All of the prison population, including the guards and officials would dine together, thus seating over 250 people.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The food served at Alcatraz was reportedly the best in the United States prison system.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The Recreation Yard was the yard used by inmates of the prison between 1934 and 1963.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] It is located opposite the dining hall south of the end of D-Block, facing the mainland on a raised level surrounded by a high wall and fence above it.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Guard Tower #3 lay just to the west of the yard.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The gun gallery was situated in the yard, mounted on one of the dining hall's exterior walls.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] In 1936, the previously dirt-covered yard was paved.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The yard was part of the most violent escape attempt from Alcatraz in May 1946 when a group of inmates hatched a plot to obtain the key into the recreation yard, kill the tower guards, take hostages, and use them as shields to reach the dock.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Inmates were permitted out into the yard on Saturdays and Sundays and on holidays for a maximum of 5 hours.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Inmates who worked seven days a week in the kitchen were rewarded with short yard breaks during the weekdays.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Badly behaved prisoners were liable to having their yard access rights taken away from them on weekends.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] The prisoners of Alcatraz were permitted to play games such as baseball, softball and other sports at these times and intellectual games such as chess.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Because of the small size of the yard and the diamond at the end of it, a section of the wall behind the first base had to be padded to cushion the impact of inmates overrunning it.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Inmates were provided gloves, bats, and balls, but no sport uniforms.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] In 1938, there were four amateur teams, the Bees, Oaks, Oilers, and Seals, named after Minor League clubs, and four league teams named after Major League clubs, the Cardinals, Cubs, Giants, and Tigers.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p01] Many of the inmates used weekends in the yards to converse with each other and discuss crime, the only real opportunities they had during the week for a durable conversation.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] The Warden's House is located at the northeastern end of the Main Cellblock, next to Alcatraz Island Lighthouse.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] The 3-floor 15-room mansion was built in 1921 according to the Golden Gate National Recreational Area signpost, although some sources say it was built in 1926 or 1929 and had 17 or 18 rooms.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] Between 1934 and 1963, the four wardens of Alcatraz resided here, including the first warden, James A.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] A house of luxury, in stark contrast to the jail next to it, the wardens often held lavish cocktail parties here.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] The signpost at the spot shows a photograph of a trusted inmate doing chores at the house for the warden and that the house had a terraced garden and greenhouse.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] The mansion had tall windows, providing fine views of San Francisco Bay.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] Today, the house is a ruin, burned down by Native Americans during the Occupation of Alcatraz on June 1, 1970.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] Building 64 Residential Apartments was the first building constructed on the island of Alcatraz, intended entirely for the purpose of accommodating the military officers and their families living on the island.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] Located next to the dock on the southeastern side of the island, below the Warden's House, the three-story apartment block was built in 1905 on the site of a U.S.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] Army barracks which had been there from the 1860s.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] It functioned as the Military Guard Barracks from 1906 until 1933.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] One of its largest apartments in the southwest corner was known as the "Cow Palace" and a nearby alleyway was known as "Chinatown".
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] The Social Hall, also known as the Officers' Club, was a social club located on the northwestern side of the island.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] Located in proximity to the Power House, water tower and Former Military Chapel (Bachelor Quarters), it formerly housed the post exchange.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] The club was a social venue for the Federal Penitentiary workers and their families on the island to unwind after locking up Alcatraz's criminals at 17:30.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] It was burned down by Native Americans during the Occupation of Alcatraz in 1970, leaving a shell which still remains.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] The club had a small bar, library, large dining and dance floor, billiards table, ping pong table and a two-lane bowling alley, and was the centre of social life on the island for the employees of the penitentiary.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] It regularly hosted dinners, bingo events, and from the 1940s onwards showed movies every Sunday night after they had been shown to the inmates during the day on Saturday and Sunday.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] The club was responsible for organizing numerous special events on the island (held either in the hall or the Parade Grounds) and the fundraising associated with it, anything from ice cream and watermelon feasts to Halloween fancy dress and Christmas parties.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] The Power House is located on the northwest coast of Alcatraz Island.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] It was constructed in 1939 for $186,000 as part of a $1.1 million modernization scheme which also included the water tower, New Industries Building, officers quarters and remodeling of the D-block.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] The white powerhouse smokestack and lighthouse were said to give an "appearance of a ship's mast on either side of the island".
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] Only Government permitted within 200 yards" lay in front of the powerhouse to deter people landing on the island at the point.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] Between 1939 and 1963, it supplied power to the Federal Penitentiary and other buildings on the island.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] The powerhouse had a tower duty station which was guarded with a "30-caliber Winchester rifle with 50 rounds of ammunition, a 1911 semiautomatic pistol with three seven-round magazines, three gas grenades, and a gas mask".
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] The water tower is located on the northwestern side of the island, near Tower No.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] 3, beyond the Morgue and Recreation Yard.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] The water tank is situated on six cross-braced steel legs submerged in concrete foundations.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] As Alcatraz had no water supply of its own, it had to import it from the mainland, brought by tug and barge.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] During the island's military years, there were in-ground water tanks and water tanks were situated on the roof of the citadel.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] The water tower was built in 1940–41 by the Federal Bureau of Prisons, after the island received a government renovations grant to supply the majority of the island's fresh water.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] It is the tallest building on the island, at a height of 94 feet (29 m) with a volume of 250,000 US gallons (950 kL) gallons of fresh water.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] It was used to store potable water for drinking, water for firefighting, and water for the island's service laundry facility.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] The Model Industries Building is a three/four-story building on the northwest corner of Alcatraz Island.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] This building was originally built by the U.S. military and was used as a laundry building until the New Industries Building was built as part of a redevelopment program on Alcatraz in 1939 when it was a federal penitentiary.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] As part of the Alcatraz jail, it held workshops for inmates to work in.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] On January 10, 1935, the building shifted to within 2.5 feet from the edge of the cliff following a landslide caused by a severe storm.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] Johnston, proposed to extend the seawall next to it and asked the bureau for $6500 to fund it.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] He would later claim to dislike the building because it was irregularly shaped.
[src:adx-florence/alcatraz-federal-penitentiary-p02] A smaller, cheaper riprap was completed by the end of 1935.
